ast Asian countries  (project until 2017)</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Russian Federation</td><td>Hosting workshop</td><td>Regional workshop on draft ISPMs, Russian speaking countries</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>United Kingdom</td><td>1 staff member</td><td>To support CPM-8 preparation (2 weeks)</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>United Kingdom</td><td>Financial contribution to Trust Fund for capacity development</td><td>Translation of PCE into Arabic and Russian</td></tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#fafafa;\"><b>Regional Plant Protection Organizations</b></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr><td>APPPC, EPPO, IAPSC, PPPO, OIRSA and COSAVE</td><td>Organizational assistance</td><td>Regional workshops on draft ISPMs in each region</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>APPPC</td><td>Organization and funding for some meeting participants</td><td>Regional workshop</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>APPPC</td><td>Organization and funding for some meeting participants</td><td>IRSS symposium</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>OIRSA and COSAVE</td><td>Workshop-funding</td><td>Regional workshops</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>COSAVE</td><td>Hosted and financed the meeting</td><td>The 25th Technical Consultation among RPPOs</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>EPPO</td><td>Hosted the meeting</td><td>ePhyto workshop + TPDP meeting arrangements.  Support for CPM8  cocktail event</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>NAPPO</td><td>1 staff member</td><td>CPM-8 preparation (2 weeks); support for CPM-8 cocktail</td></tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#fafafa;\"><b>Collaborative programmes</b></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr><td>Several contracting parties, regional organizations and international organizations</td><td>Hosted meeting (ongoing)</td><td>EWGs, TPs and workshops</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Several contracting parties, regional organizations and international organizations</td><td>Organized meetings (ongoing)</td><td>Workshops</td></tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','474'),(344,'**Convention text, model instruments and related information**\r\n\r\n\r\nIPPC - the International Plant Protection Convention - is an international treaty that aims to secure coordinated, effective action to prevent and to control the introduction and spread of pests of plants and plant products.\r\n\r\n The Convention extends beyond the protection of cultivated plants to the protection of natural flora and plant products. It takes into consideration both direct and indirect damage by pests, so it includes weeds. It also covers vehicles, aircraft and vessels, containers, storage places, soil and other objects or material that can harbour or spread pests. \r\n\r\nThe Convention provides a framework and a forum for international cooperation, harmonization and technical exchange between contracting parties. \r\n\r\nIts implementation involves collaboration by National Plant Protection Organizations (NPPOs) ? the official services established by governments to discharge the functions specified by the IPPC ? and Regional Plant Protection Organizations (RPPOs), which can act as coordinating bodies at a regional level to achieve the objectives of the IPPC. \r\n\r\nThe convention has been deposited with the Director-General of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) since its adoption in 1951.','54'),(345,'[International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs)](/standards) are the standards adopted by the [Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM)](/core-activities/governance/cpm), which is the governing body of the IPPC. The IPPC is the only standard setting organization for plant health.  In addition, these standards, guidelines and recommendations are recognized as the basis for phytosanitary measures applied in trade by the Members of the World Trade Organization under the Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures (the SPS Agreement).\r\n\r\nBoth contracting and non-contracting parties to the IPPC are encouraged to implement these standards.\r\n\r\nStandards in themselves are not regulatory instruments but come into force once countries establish requirements within their national legislation. Requests for specific information on import requirements should be addressed to the [national plant protection organizations (NPPOs)](/countries/contactpoints) of the country of import.\r\n\r\n## The IPPC Standard Setting Procedure\r\n\r\nThe IPPC Standard Setting Procedure was revised and adopted by CPM-7 (2012), see Appendix 5 of the [CPM-7 (2012) report](/node/19088) for the IPPC Standard setting procedure.In this procedure, IPPC members are defined as: Contracting parties, National Plant Protection Organizations (NPPOs), Regional Plant Protection Organizations (RPPOs) and relevant international organizations.\r\n \r\nThe IPPC Standard Setting Procedure consists of the followingfour stages:\r\n\r\n### Stage 1: Developing the List of topics for IPPC standards\r\n\r\nThe IPPC Secretariat requests IPPC members* to submit topics for IPPC standards. The [Standards Committee (SC)](/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee) reviews and prioritizes the topics and recommends the changes to the CPM.  The [List of topics for IPPC standards (LOT)] (/core-activities/standards-setting/list-topics-ippc-standards) is adopted by the CPM.  The SC reviews and approves [specifications](/core-activities/standards-setting/approved-specifications-draft-ispms-under-development) for each topic that outlines what the ISPM should address.\r\n\r\n### Stage 2: Drafting\r\n\r\nIPPC members identify and nominate [technical experts](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups) that are approved by the SC to develop the draft ISPM.\r\n\r\n### Stage 3: Member consultation\r\n\r\nThe SC approves the draft ISPM and submits it for [member consultation](/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms) and contracting parties provide comments to the IPPC Secretariat using the [IPPC Online Comment System (OCS)](http://ocs.ippc.int/). A working group consisting of seven SC members (SC-7) reviews the comments and revises the draft ISPM as appropriate and is made available for the [substantial concerns commenting period (SCCP)](/core-activities/standards-setting/substantial-concerns-commenting-period-sccp-draft-ispms). Taking into the account the comments from the SCCP, the SC recommends the draft standard to the CPM for adoption. \r\n\r\n### Stage 4: Adoption and publication\r\n\r\nDraft ISPMs are submitted to the CPM for adoption, if a contracting party opposes the adoption they must submit a formal objection to the IPPC Secretariat at least 14 days prior to the CPM and the draft is returned to the SC for further guidance.  [Adopted standards](/standards) are published [on the IPP](/standards).\r\n\r\nFor Diagnostic Protocols (DPs), the CPM-7 (2012) adopted IPPC standard setting process (see Appendix 5 of the [CPM-7 (2012) report](/publications/cpm-7-report-2012)) delegated its authority to the Standard Committee (SC) to adopt DPs on its behalf. Once the SC approves a DP it is subject to a 45-day notification period, which take place twice a year: between 1 July - 15 August and between 15 December - 30 January.  During this 45-day notification period, contracting parties may submit a formal objections and the draft is returned to the SC for further guidance.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-24 by Brent Larson. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:brent.larson@fao.org\">brent.larson@fao.org.</a></div>','62'),(346,'This page includes all adopted International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs). ## [Jump to the Standards, below](#block-agenda-items-list) &darr; **NOTES** 2014-09-03: **ISPM 12:2011 in English has been reposted today** because the **title of Appendix 1 was corrected** (En version only). We became aware of an error that had occurred after adoption (of the correct title) and consequently modified the title to reflect what CPM adopted. We apologise for the inconvenience.** 2014-04-29: ISPM 11:2013 and ISPM 15:2009 adopted at CPM-8 and revised by the Chinese, French, Russian and Spanish Language Review Groups have been re-posted to reflect the changes noted by CPM-9. 2013-08-26: Ink amendments as noted by CPM-8 (2013) were applied to: ISPM 5 and Supplement 2 to ISPM 5, ISPM 9, ISPM 15, ISPM 16, ISPM 17, ISPM 20, ISPM 23, and ISPM 25 (English only). The English version of ISPMs adopted before CPM-7 (2012) (posted on 2011-12-15) have been reformatted and ink amendments from CPM-5 (2010) and CPM-6 (2011) have been incorporated. **EXPANDABLE LAYOUT** Previous versions of adopted ISPMs as well as translations into non-official FAO languages (via copublishing agreements) are available by clicking on the \"Show details\" tab of each ISPM row. **DOWNLOAD MULTIPLE STANDARDS** To download some or all Standards, scroll to the bottom of the page and click \"Download multiple files\", tick the boxes of the files you wish to download and click \"Create an archive of selected files\". **TERMS OF USE** The designations employed and the presentation of material in this information product do not imply the expression of any opinion whatsoever on the part of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) concerning the legal or development status of any country, territory, city or area or of its authorities, or concerning the delimitation of its frontiers or boundaries. The mention of specific companies or products of manufacturers, whether or not these have been patented, does not imply that these have been endorsed or recommended by FAO in preference to others of a similar nature that are not mentioned. The views expressed in this information product are those of the author(s) and do not necessarily reflect the views of FAO. FAO encourages the use, reproduction and dissemination of material in this information product. Except where otherwise indicated, material may be copied, downloaded and printed for private study, research and teaching purposes, or for use in non-commercial products or services, provided that appropriate acknowledgement of FAO as the source and copyright holder is given and that FAO?s endorsement of users? views, products or services is not implied in any way. All requests for translation and adaptation rights, and for resale and other commercial use rights should be made via www.fao.org/contact-us/licence-request or addressed to copyright@fao.org. FAO information products are available on the FAO website (www.fao.org/publications) and can be purchased through publications-sales@fao.org. **&copy; FAO 2011** <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-10-08 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','63'),(347,'_[Construction of the Tower of Babel](http://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/asset-viewer/the-tower-of-babel/bAGKOdJfvfAhYQ?projectId=art-project) by [Pieter Bruegel (Brueghel) the Elder](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pieter_Brueghel_the_Elder), 1563._ The established Language Review Groups are invited to review ISPMs adopted at CPM meetings and to submit comments through their coordinator to the IPPC Secretariat within 3 months since they have been advised that the adopted ISPMs have been published on IPP. The CPM-8 agreed to allow 7 months to the LRG for Russian to review the standards adopted at its session. For detailed information and guidance on the LRG procedure, please see the document ?Procedure to correct errors in International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs) in language versions other than English after adoption?, posted below as amended at CPM-8. Should a member wish to join a LRG, please contact the appropriate LRG Coordinator (contact details below) and use the form which can be downloaded from this site. --- **Chinese LRG** **Coordinator: Mr Liu Hui** Ministry of Agriculture No. 20 Mai Zi Dian Street, 100125 Beijing, China Phone: +86 10-59194524 Email: <liu_hui@agri.gov.cn> **TPG focal point for Chinese**: Ms Hong Ning - <ninghong2006@aliyun.com> --- **French LRG** **Coordinator: Mr Lucien K. Kouam?** Minist?re de l?Agriculture 01 B.P.944 Abidjan, C?te d?Ivoire Phone: +225 20218442 / +225 07903754 Email: <l_kouame@yahoo.fr> **TPG focal point for French**: Ms Laurence BOUHOT-DELDUC - <laurence.bouhot-delduc@agriculture.gouv.fr> --- **Russian LRG** **Coordinator: Vacant** **TPG focal point for Russian**: Mr Andrei Orlinski - <Orlinski@eppo.fr> --- **Spanish LRG** **Coordinator: Ms Beatriz Melcho** Comit? de Sanidad Vegetal del Cono Sur (COSAVE) Av. Paseo Col?n 315, C1063ACD, Buenos Aires, Argentina Email: bmelcho@cosave.org **TPG focal point for Spanish**: Beatriz Melcho - <bmelcho@mgap.gub.uy> Note: in order to join the Spanish LRG, Spanish speaking new members should contact their respective NPPO. Other interested potential members should contact the LRG^s coordinator. --- 2013-04-24: The ISPMs adopted at CPM-8 were posted under the Adopted Standards section. These versions will be updated after the review by the Language Review Groups for Chinese, French, Russian and Spanish. --- <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-05-08 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','85'),(348,'Explanatory documents for International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs) are produced as a result of a decision of the Interim Commission on Phytosanitary Measures in 2004. They are written to provide supporting information for the standard to which they refer and are not an official legal interpretation of the IPPC or its related documents, and are produced for public information purposes only. Each document is written by an expert, reviewed by at least two peers (usually from the Expert Working Group concerned), then reviewed by the Standards Committee and the IPPC Secretariat. However, the material presented in explanatory documents remains the opinion of the writer and cannot be interpreted as a decision of the CPM. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-04-29 by C?line Germain. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:celine.germain@fao.org\">celine.germain@fao.org.</a><br></p> ','445'),(349,'<div class=\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=\"field-items\"><div class=\"field-item even\"><p>Any country that wishes to translate the International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures, after adoption by the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures, into their local language, is encouraged to do so under a copublishing agreement with FAO.</p><p>Translations of the IPPC standards under copublishing agreements are a means to reach out to as many stakeholders as possible, and the advantages of a such an agreement are numerous: recognition of the work by the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures, guidance and assistance from the IPPC Secretariat when possible, information on the adoption of new standards, and access to the Online Phytosanitary Glossary (ISPM 5). For the IPPC Secretariat, the advances include consistency among languages through sharing of information.</p><p>To raise the agreement, we need to receive contact details of the institution and person signing (full name, title, address, email and phone number). We will then send a draft agreement to be reviewed by the potential copublisher. Once agreement is reached, we will send the final document for signature and return it signed as well. The copublisher will hereafter be informed when standards are adopted, and receive them in MS Word format (they are normally published only in PDF).</p><p>The unofficial translations of the standards are available under the individual standard on the Adopted Standards page: <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/ispms\">https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/ispms</a></p><p>The following countries currently have copublishing agreements with FAO:</p><p><strong>- Brazil (2009)</strong></p><p><strong>- Japan (2009)</strong></p><p><strong>- Korea (2010)</strong></p><p><strong>- Viet Nam (2012)</strong></p><p><strong>- Germany (2013)</strong></p><p><strong>- Thailand (2014)</strong></p><p>For queries of comments regarding the contents of this page, please contact <a href=\"mailto:Eva.Moller@fao.org\">Eva.Moller@fao.org</a> Page last updated 2014-08-21.</p></div></div></div><p>&nbsp;</p>','27478'),(350,'*The IPPC Standards Committee (SC) and Secretariat in May 2014* The first session of the [Commission on Phytosanitary Measures](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/governance/cpm) (CPM-1 (2006)) established the Standards Committee (SC). The SC consists of 25 members from each of the seven FAO regions: four members each from Africa, Asia, Europe, Latin America and the Caribbean, and Near East; two from North America; and three from Southwest Pacific. The current membership of the Standards Committee is posted below. ## The SC is responsible for: - overseeing the <a href=\"index.php?id=13352\">IPPC Standard Setting Process</a> - managing the development of <a href=\"index.php?id=13399\">International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs)</a> - providing guidance and oversight to the work of <a href=\"index.php?id=179728\">Technical Panels&nbsp;(TPs)</a> and <a href=\"index.php?id=179725\">Expert Working Groups (EWGs)</a> </ul><strong>The Standards Committee Working Group (SC-7)</strong> Seven SC members (one from each region) are selected by the SC to form the SC Working Group (SC-7). The SC-7 supports the work of the SC in the detailed consideration of draft ISPMs and specifications. ## The SC-7 is responsible for: - examining all of the substantive member comments (including proposed amendments) from <a href=\"index.php?id=207803\">member consultation on draft ISPMs</a>, identified by the steward - reviewing and revising draft ISPMs prepared by the stewards in response to member comments and proposing revisions to the SC - drafting SC responses to substantive member comments not incorporated into the draft ISPM, as identified by the steward - proposing which changes to draft ISPM should be considered further by the SC - explaining the proposed revisions to draft ISPMs to the SC as required - performing other functions regarding draft standards and specifications as directed by the SC <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-03-24 by C?line Germain. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:celine.germain@fao.org\">celine.germain@fao.org.</a><br></p>','76'),(351,'Draft ISPMs are developed by expert drafting groups (EDGs). EDGs draft or revise standards in accordance with the relevant specification. There are two types of EDGs: [expert working groups (EWGs)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups) and [technical panels (TPs)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels). EWGs usually meet only once to draft or revise a standard. TPs meet on a regular basis (usually annually) and are responsible for the development of specific standards related to the technical area of the TP. There are five TPs: - [Technical panel on diagnostic protocols (TPDP)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-diagnostic-protocols) - [Technical panel on forest quarantine (TPFQ)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-forest-quarantine) - [Technical panel on fruit flies (TPFF)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-fruit-flies) - [Technical panel for the Glossary (TPG)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-glossary-phytosanitary-terms-ispm-5) - [Technical panel on phytosanitary treatments (TPPT)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-phytosanitary-treatments) ','468'),(352,'In an effort to improve the quality and efficiency in the development of ISPMs, the ICPM-6 (2004) approved the establishment of technical panels (TPs) under the supervision of the [Standards Committee (SC)](/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee). The TPs, established for specific phytosanitary technical areas, develop ISPMs and provide guidance to the SC regarding specific phytosanitary issues. A steward, who is usually a member of the SC, supports and guides members in the development of draft ISPMs. The SC then reviews, revises and recommends the draft ISPM for [member consultation](/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms). The SC selects TP members after a call for experts and each TP member is selected for a five year term. The SC annually reviews the progress of the TP and considers issues regarding the panel&rsquo;s work programme, its relationship to other panels and its organization. Currently, there are five TPs: - [Technical panel on diagnostic protocols (TPDP)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-diagnostic-protocols) - [Technical panel on forest quarantine (TPFQ)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-forest-quarantine) - [Technical panel on fruit flies (TPFF)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-fruit-flies) - [Technical panel for the Glossary (TPG)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-glossary-phytosanitary-terms-ispm-5) - [Technical panel on phytosanitary treatments (TPPT)](/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-phytosanitary-treatments) <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-24 by Adriana Moreira. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:adriana.moreira@fao.org\">adriana.moreira@fao.org.</a><br></p>','451'),(353,'The **Technical Panel on Pest Free Areas and Systems Approaches for Fruit Flies (TPFF)** was established to review scientific and technical data and to draft ISPMs in support of international agricultural trade through the establishment of pest free areas and systems approaches for fruit flies. The TPFF is composed of an international group of phytosanitary experts with interest and expertise in relevant aspects of plant quarantine, control and risk management of fruit flies. TPFF members are nominated by [NPPOs](/countries) and [RPPOs](/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations) and selected by the [Standards Committee (SC)](/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee). The current membership of the TPFF is posted below. As of June 2013, the TPFF has developed the following adopted standards: - [**ISPM 26:2006** Establishment of pest free areas for fruit flies](/publications/establishment-pest-free-areas-fruit-flies-tephritidae) - [**ISPM 30:2008** Establishment of areas of low pest prevalence for fruit flies (Tephritidae)](/publications/establishment-areas-low-pest-prevalence-fruit-flies-tephritidae) - [**Appendix 1 (2011) to ISPM 30:** Fruit fly trapping](/publications/establishment-areas-low-pest-prevalence-fruit-flies-tephritidae) - [**ISPM 35:2012** Systems approach for pest risk management of fruit flies (Tephritidae)](/publications/systems-approach-pest-risk-management-fruit-flies-tephritidae) The panel has also developed the following draft ISPMs: - Determining the host status of fruits and vegetables to fruit fly (Tephritidae)&nbsp;infestations (2006-031) - Phytosanitary Procedures for Fruit Fly (Tephritidae) Management (2005-010) - Establishment and maintenance of fruit fly quarantine areas within a pest free area in the event of outbreak detection (2009-007) <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-03-12 by Stephanie Dubon. For more information, please contact her at <a href=\"mailto:Stephanie.Dubon@fao.org\">Stephanie.Dubon@fao.org.</a><br></p>','487'),(354,'The **Technical Panel for the Glossary (TPG)** was established in 2006 and took the succession of the former Glossary Working Group, which had been working on matters relating to ISPM 5: *[Glossary of phytosanitary terms](/publications/glossary-phytosanitary-terms)* since 1994. The TPG works on matters related to ISPM 5, which is a reference standard listing harmonized terms, definitions and abbreviations in Arabic, Chinese, English, French and Spanish. The TPG reviews the Glossary based on needs identified by various groups or arising from the establishment or amendment of ISPMs, and make recommendations for amendments. It also deals with other issues associated with the technical language of standards, as required by the CPM or Standards Committee. Among its regular tasks, it reviews proposals for new or revised terms/definitions, reviews ISPMs for consistency of terms within and between ISPMs, undertake duties concerning the use of technical language in standards and associated publications. The TPG is currently composed of experts with knowledge of phytosanitary systems and together representing all FAO languages, and includes a steward who is member of the Standards Committee. The membership of the TPG is indicated in a document below under &ldquo;Publications&rdquo;. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-19 by Fabienne Grousset. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:fabienne.grousset@fao.org\">fabienne.grousset@fao.org.</a><br></p> ','486'),(355,'The <b>Technical Panel on Forest Quarantine (TPFQ)</b> is composed of eight members, a steward, and an assistant steward. The steward and assistant steward are representatives of the <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee\">Standards Committee (SC)</a>. The TPFQ deals with technical matters regarding forest quarantine issues. It also works closely with the other technical panels (TPs), particularly the TP on Phytosanitary Treatments (TPPT) in developing guidance related to treatment for forest commodities. The TPFQ^s primary function is reviewing relevant technical and scientific information to provide guidance to the SC as requested on development, amendment and revision of standards relating to forest quarantine. One member of the TPFQ is also the Chair of <a href=\"/partners/international-organizations/international-forestry-quarantine-research-group\">International Forestry Research Group (IFQRG)</a>. IFQRG provides scientific and technical information resulting from analysis of complex phytosanitary issues. Reports from TPFQ meetings and the current membership of the panel are posted below. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-03-19 by Mike Ormsby. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:michael.ormsby@fao.org\">michael.ormsby@fao.org.</a><br></p>','485'),(356,'*Photo: TPDP members at their 2013 June meeting in Paris, France hosted by EPPO.* Left to right (up): Ms Antoinette SWART (South Africa - Invited expert on Ditylenchus), Ms Liping YIN (CHN), Ms Natasa MEHLE (Slovenia - Invited expert by the meeting host), Mr Delano JAMES (CAN), Mr Brendan RODONI (AUS), Mr Robert TAYLOR (NZL), Ms G?raldine ANTHOINE (FRA), Ms Jane CHARD (GBR). Left to right (down): Ms Fabienne GROUSSET (IPPC Secretariat), Ms Adriana MOREIRA (IPPC Secretariat), Ms Fran?oise PETTER (EPPO Secretariat). <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">THE IPPC TECHNICAL PANEL ON DIAGNOSTIC PROTOCOLS (TPDP)</a><br></p> The **Technical panel on diagnostic protocols (TPDP)** was established in 2004. Diagnostic protocols are produced as annexes to [ISPM 27 - Diagnostic protocols for regulated pests](/publications/diagnostic-protocols-regulated-pests). The TPDP proposes priorities for protocols to be developed on specific pest species or group of species, identifies specialists to develop each protocol, supervises the production of diagnostic protocols, and considers other topics related to diagnosis of regulated pests. Further information on the TPDP working procedures can be found in the IPPC Procedure Manual for standard setting. You can download a copy of the 2013 IPPC Procedure Manual - Standard Setting by [clicking here](https://www.ippc.int/sites/default/files/documents/20140110/ippcproceduremanual_stset_2014-01-10_2014011009%3A19--3.75%20MB.pdf). On January 2014, there are 32 protocols on the work programme of the TPDP at different stages of development, from initiation of drafting to adoption. The subjects of TPDP work and their stage of development can be found at the [List of Topics for IPPC Standards](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/list-topics-ippc-standards). Each protocol deals with one pest species or group of species, in the following categories: bacteria; fungi and fungus-like organisms; insects and mites; nematodes; plants; viruses and phytoplasmas. The TPDP is composed of diagnostic experts, with a lead for each of the discipline mentioned above, plus a steward who is member of the Standards Committee (SC). The membership of the TPDP is indicated in a document below under ?Publications?. Up to now, **six diagnostic protocols have been adopted by the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM)**: - DP 1: [*Thrips palmi*](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-1-2010-thrips-palmi-karny) - DP 2: [*Plum pox virus*](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-2-2012-plum-pox-virus) - DP 3: [*Trogoderma granarium*](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-3-2012-trogoderma-granarium-everts) - DP 4: [*Tilletia indica* Mitra](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-4-2014-tilletia-indica-mitra) - DP 5: [*Phyllosticta citricarpa* (McAlpine) Aa on fruit](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-5-2014-phyllosticta-citricarpa-mcalpine-aa-fruit) - DP 6: [*Xanthomonas citri* subsp. *citri*](https://www.ippc.int/publications/dp-6-2014-xanthomonas-citri-subsp-citri) <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">LATEST NEWS!</a><br></p> **1. New adopted Diagnostic protocols** The Standards Committee (SC) on behalf of the CPM has adopted two diagnostic protocols: - *Phyllosticta citricarpa* (McAlpine) Aa on fruit (2004-023) - *Xanthomonas citri* subsp. *citri* (2004-011). The two draft diagnostic protocols (DPs) were approved by the SC for the 45-days notification period, which closed on 15 August 2014. More information on the Notification Period are available at the IPP by [clicking here](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/draft-ispms/notification-period-dps). **2. Member Consultation on Draft Diagnostic Protocols:** The SC approved the following draft diagnostic protocols for member consultation starting in 01 July 2014 to 30 November 2014. More information are available in the [2014 SC May meeting report](https://www.ippc.int/publications/2014-05-report-standards-committee). 1. *Erwinia amylovora* (2004-009) 2. *Ditylenchus destructor* and *Ditylenchus dipsaci* (2004-017) 3. Genus *Anastrepha* (2004-015) 4. Phytoplasmas (2004-018) More information on the Member Consultation on Draft Diagnostic Protocols can be found by [clicking here](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms). **3. New updated version of the Instructions to Authors** - **2014-08-28**: As it was agreed during the 2014 July TPDP meeting,**the Template tables for description of PCR,RT-PCR or PRC-RFLP reactions** was included to the Instructions for Authors as an **Appendix 5**. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-08-19 by Yosra Chabaane. For further information please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:yosra.chabaane@fao.org\">yosra.chabaane@fao.org</a> or to <a href=\"mailto:adriana.moreira@fao.org\">adriana.moreira@fao.org</a><br></p> ','484'),(357,'<p>The <strong>Technical Panel on Phytosanitary Treatments (TPPT)</strong> evaluates data submissions from <a href=\"/countries\">NPPOs</a> and <a href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations\">RPPOs</a> and reviews, revises and develops phytosanitary treatments. The TPPT also provides guidance to the <a href=\"/node/63\">Standards Committee (SC)</a> regarding specific phytosanitary treatment issues. The TPPT is composed of nine members and a steward. The steward is a representative of the <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee\">Standards Committee</a>. The TPPT also works closely with the other TPs, particularly the <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-forest-quarantine\">TP on Forest Quarantine (TPFQ)</a> in developing guidance related to treatments on forest commodities. Reports from TPPT meetings are available below.</p><p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-02-06. For more information, please contact <a href=\"mailto:nuri.niyazi@fao.org\"><span style=\"color:#0000ff;\"><u>nuri.niyazi@fao.org</u></span></a><span style=\"color:#0000ff;\">.</span></p>','490'),(358,'Once the [Standards Committee (SC)](/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee) approves a [specification](/core-activities/standards-setting/approved-specifications-draft-ispms-under-development) and resources are identified to hold an expert working group (EWG) meeting, the IPPC Secretariat contacts [national plant protection organizations (NPPOs)](/countries/contactpoints) and [Regional Plant Protection Organizations (RPPOs)](/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations) to nominate experts to be members of the EWG to develop a draft ISPM. The SC selects the technical experts identified by the NPPOs and RPPOs for the EWG. The EWG meets and produces a draft ISPM and a meeting report. The draft ISPM is then approved for [member consultation](/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms) by the SC. EWGs have 6?10 participants that represent a wide geographic area (including proportional developing country participation) and a member from the SC, if possible (e.g. a steward). Meeting Reports from EWGs are posted below. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-19 by C?line Germain. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:celine.germain@fao.org\">celine.germain@fao.org.</a><br></p>','450'),(359,'[Jump to Publications ?](#public-publications) **The following outline is a brief summary of the events to date in the development of the draft ISPM on Minimizing pest movement by sea containers. More details are given in the document posted below: \"Background information: development of the draft ISPM on Sea Containers (2008-001)\". All related meeting reports, presentations and documents are also posted at the bottom of this page for further reference. Several background documents on sea containers (documents on the biosecurity risk and its management, examples of management programs, pest risk assessment of insects in sea cargo containers, etc...) that were provided by some NPPOs are also available through this [link](https://www.ippc.int/node/27777)** ## 2014-04 CPM-9 (2014) decisions on the topic Minimizing pest movement by sea containers (2008-001) **CPM-9 (2014) agreed to the following statement:** \"The CPM: - recognised and appreciated the **joint initiative by the International Maritime Organization (IMO), the International Labour Organization (ILO) and United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) of revising the Code of Practice for Packing of Cargo Transport Units (CTU Code)**. With the support from the IPPC Expert Working Group on Sea Containers, those organizations have incorporated into the revised CTU Code several elements of phytosanitary relevance, e.g. information on pests and other contamination which may be associated with CTUs, as well as very useful practical guidelines for cleanliness, cleaning, packing and handling; - welcomed the [recent adoption of the CTU Code by UNECE](http://www.unece.org/index.php?id=35067) and looked forward to the adoption also by IMO and ILO of the revised CTU Code later this year; - emphasised that the careful implementation of the revised CTU Code by all operators responsible for and involved in the packing and handling of sea containers is crucial for preventing the spread of pests and invasive alien species.\" THe CPM also also: - noted that the SC will discuss the comments from member consultation and how to proceed with the development of the ISPM on Minimizing pest movement by sea containers (2008-001), including the possible need for further survey work; - encouraged contracting parties and the IPPC Secretariat to liaise with national and international counterparts respectively to express their appreciation for the work done by IMO/ILO/UNECE and seek further collaboration; and - requested the Secretariat in association with the EU, USA, Japan, Argentina and Gabon to prepare a draft recommendation for possible adoption at CPM-10 - requested the Secretary to send the statements above to the heads of IMO, ILO and UNECE. ##2014-02 Draft industry guidance - IMO/ILO/UNECE Code of Practice for Packing of Cargo Transport Units (CTU Code) - endorsed by UNECE As mentioned below in the section regarding the 2012 May Expert Working Group (EWG) meeting, industry guidance in the form of a Code of Practice for Packing of Cargo Transport Units has been updated jointly by the International Maritime Organization (IMO), the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) and the International Labour Organization (ILO). The Sea Containers EWG provided input into this guidance so it could include phytosanitary requirements for cleaning sea containers. The [January 2014 version of the Code of Practice for Packing of Cargo Transport Units (CTUs)](http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/doc/2014/itc/id_07_CTU_Code_January_2014.pdf) is posted below for information (not open for commenting). It has been endorsed by the [Inland Transport Committee (25 to 27 February 2014) of the UNECE]((http://www.unece.org/index.php?id=35067)). It will be presented later to IMO and ILO. The specific parts of interest are chapter 3, chapter 4 (section 4.2.10), chapter 8 (sections 8.2.4.4, 8.3.2.4 and 8.3.2.5) and Annex 13. ## 2013-12 Compiled comments on the 2013 member consultation The IPPC Secretariat compiled the comments received during the 2013 member consultation on the preliminary draft standard on sea containers and sent them to the steward. The compiled comments are available by clicking [this link](https://www.ippc.int/publications/2013-compiled-comments-draft-ispm-minimizing-pest-movement-sea-containers-2008-001). They will be considered in detail by the Standards Committee in their 2014 May meeting. ## 2013-11 SC discussion and decisions (See meeting report posted below: section 4.1) An update was given by the subgroup of the SC who had been charged, in the 2013 May SC meeting, with developing a survey for NPPOs on the rate of pest interceptions on sea containers and an accompanying letter. This SC subgroup had completed their tasks but had also requested the support of two statisticians from the USA and New Zealand. The statisticians had noted difficulties with conducting such surveys. In order to yield acceptable results that could be repeated in the future, the surveys would need to be done with the proper methodology and this could be expensive and time consuming. The SC survey group had suggested that statisticians analyse data from previous surveys from several countries (China, USA, Australia and New Zealand) and further consider if a new survey would be needed. The SC agreed that the statisticians? opinions should be carefully considered by the SC survey group before making a recommendation to CPM on whether a survey should be done. The preliminary draft ISPM on Minimizing pest movement by sea containers (2008-001) had been sent for member consultation through the OCS (1 July ? 1 December 2013): draft ISPM posted below. The SC noted that all comments on the preliminary draft ISPM will be considered during the May 2014 SC meeting (as opposed to the regular process where the SC-7 reviews member comments). The SC agreed to present an update on activities related to sea containers to CPM-9 (2014), to be prepared by the SC subgroup. ## 2013-05 SC discussion and decisions: (See meeting report posted below: sections 3.1 and 5.2) As requested by CPM-8 (2013), the SC approved for member consultation the revised preliminary draft on Minimizing pest movement by sea containers (2008-001), with the understanding that there will be a further member consultation. The SC decided that this preliminary draft would be open only for general conceptual comments on sections of text. The length of the 2013 member consultation for draft ISPMs is 150 days (1 July 2013 to 1 December 2013). ## The topic was also discussed in the following meetings: -**2013-04 CPM-8 (2013)**: see decisions in section 8.1.4 of the meeting report posted below - **2012-11 Standards Committee (SC) November 2012** (see meeting report &quot;2012-11 Report of the Standards Committee&quot;, paragraph 132 to 153) - **2012-11 Standards Committee (SC) meeting** (See 2012 November SC meeting report posted below, paragraph 132 to 153) - **2012-10 Strategic Planning Group (SPG) meeting** (see meeting report &quot;2012-10 SPG 14 REPORT&quot;, paragraph 36 to 43) - **2012-05 Expert Working Group (EWG) meeting in Malaysia** (see meeting report, &quot;2012 Report: EWG on Minimizing Pest Movement by Sea Containers (May, 2012)&quot;) - **2012-04 SC April 2012** (see meeting report, &quot;2012-04 Report of the Standards Committee&quot;) - **2012-03 CPM-7 (2012) decision and side event** (see meeting report, &quot;CPM-7 REPORT (2012)&quot; and presentation given at the side event, &quot;Presentation to CPM 7&quot;) - **2011-11 Steering Committee on Sea Containers (SCSC) Meeting Rome** (see meeting report below, &quot;2011 Report: Meeting of the Steering Committee on Sea Containers&quot;) - **2011-03 SC selected experts for Expert Working Group (EWG)** - **2010-04 SC approved Specification 51** (see link below, &quot;Specification 51: Minimizing pest movement by sea containers and conveyances in international trade&quot;) - **2010-03 CPM-5** recommended this topic be worked on as a matter of urgency - **2009-11 Standards Committee (SC)** approved draft specification for MC - **2008-03 Third meeting of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM-3)** added topic Minimizing pest movement by sea containers and conveyances (2008-001) to the List of Topics for IPPC standards. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-04-22 by C?line Germain. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:celine.germain@fao.org\">celine.germain@fao.org.</a><br></p>','10756'),(360,'The **[Online Comment System (OCS)](http://ocs.ippc.int/)** is a system for defined stakeholders to insert, save, share, and submit comments on documents; for secretariats to compile comments in an easy and efficient manner (“with the click of a button”) and to provide data for analysis.\r\n\r\n**Its mission is to provide a simple, efficient, user-friendly online system to share, submit and compile comments on documents.**\r\n\r\nThrough the OCS, IPPC Official Contact Points can submit comments on draft documents, with the support of the following optional users: Lead (one assigned per document, having the same role and functions as the Contact Point, but it cannot submit comments); Assistant (one per document, designated by the Contact Point to oversee the commenting process within the organization and to provide comments on the draft document); Reviewers (more than one per document, designated by the Contact Point or Assistant to provide comments on the draft document).\r\n\r\nTraining videos and material are available to OCS users below. \r\n\r\n**Please note that your login details may be different from the IPP ones. In order to retrieve your password, check the \"Forgot your password?\" feature in the OCS homepage.**\r\n\r\n---------------------------\r\n\r\n[IPPC Online Comments System Training Video Part I](http://youtu.be/cHiZ4GwgORc):\r\n<div>\r\n<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/cHiZ4GwgORc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n</div>\r\n[IPPC Online Comments System Training Video Part II »](http://youtu.be/7n8S3p4VoQQ)\r\n\r\n[IPPC Online Comments System Training Video Part III »](http://youtu.be/UcWPUGIgPDI)\r\n\r\n---------------------------\r\n\r\n**OCS background**\r\n\r\nThe IPPC Secretariat has developed the OCS in 2011 following a technical bid made in 2009 (original documents for the bid are kept by the IPPC Secretariat), and it has been using it since then for the following commenting periods: [member consultation on draft specifications](/node/455), [member consultation on draft ISPMs](/node/462), and [substantial concerns commenting period (SCCP)](/node/519/).\r\n\r\nIn 2014, because of the rapid evolution of online technologies and of issues with the OCS compatibility, performance and user-friendliness, the IPPC Secretariat has undertaken a review of the [OCS](http:ocs.ippc.int/index.html) user requirements. A new OCS plan has been submitted for IPPC member comments, and compiled comments with Secretariat\'s responses have been posted below on 2014-05-27.\r\n\r\nThe IPPC Secretariat is currently working on the implementation of the new OCS plan in cooperation with the Secretariat of the [Codex Alimentarius Commission](http://www.codexalimentarius.org/).\r\n\r\n---------------------------\r\n\r\n**For further information, please check the OCS user manuals or see the videos above. Alternatively, you can contact the IPPC OCS team at IPPC-OCS@fao.org.**\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">This web page was last updated on 2014-07-17 by Mirko Montuori. For further information , please email him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a></div>','504'),(361,'','521'),(362,'<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">On 17&nbsp;December 2010, the IPPC sent a letter to the Chairperson from each FAO Region regarding Nominations and submissions confirming existing members and potential replacements for the Standards Committee&nbsp;(SC) and for the Subsidiary Body on Dispute Settlement (SBDS).&nbsp;</span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Nominations or, where appropriate, confirmation of the existing members and potential replacements should be submitted by 1 February 2011.&nbsp;Submissions should be sent&nbsp;to the IPPC Secretariat, preferably by email (ippc@fao.org). Submissions may also be sent by fax (+39 06 5705 4819).</span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; layout-grid-mode: line;\" lang=\"EN-GB\"><span style=\"font-size: small; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">&nbsp;</span></span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">All nominations should include the following information:</span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Nominee&rsquo;s name, full mailing address, telephone number, fax number and e-mail address</span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Nominee&rsquo;s curriculum vitae (CV)</span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;Statement of commitment (Annex 6)</span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\">&nbsp;</p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">For&nbsp;questions, please contact Brent Larson (+39 06 5705 4915, brent.larson@fao.org) for matters related to the Standards Committee or David Nowell (+39 06 5705 2034, dave.nowell@fao.org) for matters related to the Subsidiary Body on Dispute Settlement. </span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-size: small; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">&nbsp;</span></span></p> <p style=\"margin: 0cm 14.1pt 0pt 0cm; text-align: left; tab-stops: 0cm;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">In addition, the CPM Paper on Membership and potential replacements for the Standards Committee and Subsidiary Body on Dispute Settlement can be accessed on the <a href=\"/node/60\">IPPC International Phytosanitary Portal (IPP)</a>.</p>','495'),(363,'<p>The deadline for the receipt of nominations was 1 March 2010.</p> ','489'),(364,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\nAdobe Connect is becoming a standard tool within FAO to facilitate distance work. It allows working on documents on screen while being in communication with other participants. This virtual meeting tool does not require installation of software. However, it requires the use of a headset and the previous installation of the latest version of Adobe Flash (which can be <a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/flashplayer.html\">downloaded from the Internet</a>). \r\n\r\nThe IPPC Secretariat began using virtual meeting tools with <a href=\"/node/450\">expert working groups (EWGs)</a> and <a href=\"/node/451\">technical panels (TPs)</a> in June 2011. The Secretariat can make specific arrangements with FAO Offices in countries to use these tools. \r\n\r\n\r\nPlease note that the installation and use of electronic tools may require prior approval of your organization^s IT services. \r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-24 by Mirko Montuori. For assistance in using virtual tools for IPPC meetings or if you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></div>\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/coreactivities_pages/4a624b613f.jpg','502'),(365,'','446'),(366,'In 2012, the IPPC Secretariat decided to separate the IPPC Procedural Manual into standalone sections, especially since the standard setting section (Section 3) was changing more constantly than the other sections. The IPPC Procedural Manual for Standard Setting is presented on this web page.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this manual is to provide a convenient consolidation of decisions, procedures, practices and forms used in the IPPC standard setting process. This edition of the manual includes decisions and procedures made up to and including the November 2013 Standards Committee meeting. The decisions and procedures described herein are subject to amendment by future revisions. The manual will be revised regularly to include any new decisions and procedures and to amend existing decisions and procedures as necessary.\r\n\r\nFor the purpose of clarity, all official text, is in black font. Some procedures and decision of the Commission Bureau and Standards Committee are also are in black font, with details of their source noted. Text that is in blue font is for explanatory purposes only and should not be considered to be official decisions.\r\nThe table of contents contains hyperlinks to help navigation in the electronic version of this document.\r\n\r\nPlease find below the 2013 version of the IPPC Procedural Manual for Standard Setting, in addition, any annexed forms to be filled in are also posted as separate documents to be downloaded, filled in and submitted as needed.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">This web page was last updated on 2013-12-19 by Eva Moller. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:eva.moller@fao.org\">eva.moller@fao.org.</a></div>','9297'),(367,'This page is the main root for the IPP subpages regarding the development of IPPC standards. It includes the subpages on Draft specifications, Approved specifications and Draft ISPMs. Please check the appropriate subpages in the right hand menu. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-20 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','15330'),(368,'**List of topics (LOT) = IPPC standard setting work programme** The IPPC Secretariat makes a call for topics every two years. IPPC members and <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels\">Technical Panels (TPs)</a> submit detailed proposals for new topics or for the revision of existing ISPMs to the IPPC Secretariat. **The 2013 call for topics closed on 31st August.** [Click here](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/calls-topics) to access the call for topics page. The <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/standards-committee\">Standards Committee (SC)</a>, taking into account the <em>IPPC Strategic Framework</em> and the <em>Criteria for justification and prioritization of proposed topics</em> (posted below), reviews the existing List of topics for IPPC standards and the compiled list of proposed topics. The SC recommends a revised List of topics for IPPC standards (including subjects), adding topics from the compiled list, deleting or modifying topics in the existing List of topics for IPPC standards as appropriate, giving each topic a recommended priority. The CPM reviews the List of topics for IPPC standards recommended by the SC. The CPM adopts modifications to the List of topics for IPPC standards, including assigning a priority for each topic. A revised List of topics for IPPC standards is posted on this IPP page. In any year, when a situation arises in which an ISPM is required urgently, the CPM may insert such a topic into the List of topics for IPPC standards. **A prioritized list of topics submitted to the IPPC Secretariat is available below.** Adoption dates, priorities, and statuses are subject to change based on a number of factors, including Secretariat resources. **The LOT is a living document and is posted on the IPP in languages.** It indicates: - Topic number (tracking number) - Current title of topic - Priority - Relevant strategic objective - Drafting body - Status - Steward(s) and assistant(s) - Technical Panels leads (when applicable) **NOTE**: The latest version of the LOT was posted on 29 May 2014 in English (\"En-2014-05\"), while the Arabic, French, Russian and Spanish versions were posted in June 2014. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-06-25 by Mirko Montuori. For further information please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:rmirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org</a><br></p>','461'),(369,'','14601'),(370,'<p class=\"warning floatcenter\"> 2014-01 ECDP: CLOSED. Two draft diagnostic protocols are open for comment until 24 March 2014: 1. Xanthomonas fragariae (2004-012) and 2. Sorghum halepense (L.) Pers. (2006-027). Thank you for the experts that provided comments! </p> <p class=\"warning floatcenter\"> 2014-02 ECDP: CLOSED. Two draft diagnostic protocols are open for comment until 24 April 2014: 1. Xiphinema americanumm (2004-025) and 2. Genus Liriomyza (2006-017).</p> <p class=\"warning floatcenter\"> 2014-03 ECDP: CLOSED. Two draft diagnostic protocols are open for comment until 17 May 2014: 1. Aphelenchoides besseyi, A. ritzemabosi and A. fragariae (2006-025) and 2. Bursaphelenchus xylophilus (2004-016).</p> <p class=\"warning floatcenter\"> 2014-04 ECDP: CLOSED. One draft diagnostic protocol is open for comment until 17 May 2014: 1. Citrus tristeza virus(2004-021).</p> The draft diagnostic protocols at this stage are in English only. <div class=\"highlight\"><p class=\"highlight\"><span class=\"larger\"><strong>In order to download and comment on a draft diagnostic protocol, please email to <a href=\"mailto:ippc-dp@fao.org\">ippc-dp@fao.org</a> to request access to the protocol you are interested in.</strong><br> <span> In your email, please specify:</span></span></p><ul class=\"highlight\"><li>Your institution</li><li>The draft protocol you want to comment upon </li><li>Your specific expertise in relation to this draft protocol.</li></ul><strong> Please note: All protocols posted in this page are draft documents not yet adopted. Please do not copy. </strong></div></p> <p><strong>Background:</strong> The expert consultation on draft diagnostic protocols (DPs) is an expert comment system on the International Phytosanitary Portal (IPP) with the objective to ensure improvement on quality for the development of a draft diagnostic protocol (DP), through inputs and feedback, in a scientific basis, from a wider number of experts worldwide not part of the DP drafting group. A wider consultation of experts on draft protocols in earlier stages of development is crucial to ensure the quality of the protocol and to facilitate the adoption process. </p> <p><strong>Process:</strong> IPPC diagnostic protocols are under development in the framework of <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/publications/diagnostic-protocols-regulated-pests\">ISPM 27: 2006 (Diagnostic protocols for regulated pests)</a>.The protocols are developed by a main author with support from a few experts and together make up Diagnostic Protocol (DP) drafting group. An expert group, the <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels/technical-panel-diagnostic-protocols\">Technical Panel on Diagnostic Protocols</a>, ensures that draft texts meet the requirements set for IPPC diagnostic protocols. At later stages of development, the draft IPPC protocols are submitted to members of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM, the governing body of the IPPC) for comments, and finally submitted for adoption by the Standards Committee (SC) on behalf of CPM. </p> <p><strong>Content of protocols:</strong> As provided in <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/publications/diagnostic-protocols-regulated-pests\">ISPM 27:2006</a>, IPPC diagnostic protocols give the procedures and methods for the official diagnosis of regulated pests that are relevant for international trade. They contain the minimum requirements for reliable diagnosis of the specified regulated pests, and provide flexibility to ensure that methods are appropriate for use in the full range of circumstances for which a diagnostic protocol may be used (e.g. from detection of a pest in a consignment, to surveillance, to routine diagnosis). Only methods of relevance for diagnostics are given in the protocol. The methods included in diagnostic protocols are selected on the basis of their sensitivity, specificity, and reproducibility. Information related to these factors is provided for each of these methods. </p> In order to achieve high quality of IPPC diagnostic protocols, we are seeking expert input on the protocols listed below. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\"> For information on the Expert Consultation process, please email to <a href=\"mailto:ippc-dp@fao.org\">ippc-dp@fao.org.</a> </p>*This web page was last updated on 2014-04-17 by Adriana Moreira. For general information please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:adriana.moreira@fao.org\">adriana.moreira@fao.org.</a>*<br></p>','14830'),(371,'This is the master page for Approved specifications; it includes three subsections: - [Approved specifications for draft ISPMs under development](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/approved-specifications-draft-ispms-under-development \"Approved specifications for draft ISPMs under development\") - [Approved specifications for adopted ISPMs](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/approved-specifications-draft-ispms-under-development/approved-specifications-adopted-ispms \"Approved specifications for adopted ISPMs\") - [Specifications removed from work programme](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/specifications-removed-work-programme \"Specifications removed from work programme\") <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-08-21 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','15332'),(372,'Specifications serve as a term of reference for the Expert Drafting Group (EDG) responsible for developing an ISPM and provide guidance on the scope of the standard and on the tasks expected of the EDG. Specifications for ISPMs are reviewed, revised and approved by the <a href=\"/node/63\">Standards Committee (SC)</a>. Approved specifications for adopted ISPMs are posted below. Approved specifications for draft ISPMs under development are located <a href=\"/node/439\">here</a>. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-08-20 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','507'),(373,'Specifications for ISPMs are clear and precise guidelines that an <a href=\"/node/468\">expert drafting group (EDG)</a> should follow when drafting or revising a standard. Specifications are drafted by, or under the auspices of, the IPPC Secretariat, steward and the <a href=\"/node/63\">Standards Committee</a> after direction is given by the Commission as to the standard&rsquo;s priority. The specifications are sent for <a href=\"/node/455\">member consultation</a> and then reviewed, revised and approved by the SC. Approved specifications for draft ISPMs under development are posted below. Approved specifications for adopted ISPMs are located <a href=\"/node/439\">here</a>. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-08-21 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','439'),(374,'','28487'),(375,'This is the master page for Draft ISPMs. It includes four subpages: - [Member consultation on draft ISPMs](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms \"Member consultation on draft ISPMs\") - [Substantial Concerns Commenting Period](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/substantial-concerns-commenting-period-sccp-draft-ispms \"Substantial Concerns Commenting Period\") - [Formal objections on draft IPSMs](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/formal-objections-draft-ispms-14-days-prior-cpm \"Formal objections on draft IPSMs\") - [Notification period of DPs](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/draft-ispms/notification-period-dps) <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-11-29 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','15333'),(376,'Following clearance by the Standards Committee (SC), draft standards are sent for member consultation by the IPPC Secretariat to contracting parties, national plant protection organizations (NPPOs), regional plant protection organizations (RPPOs) and international organizations. Comments must be submitted through the IPPC contact point in the IPPC Online Comment System (OCS, [ocs.ippc.int/index.html](http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html)). For more information on the OCS, please visit the [OCS page on the IPP](/node/504). Please contact the IPPC Secretariat (IPPC-OCS@fao.org) for assistance using the OCS. The SC in May 2014 approved the following draft ISPMs for member consultation: - 1994-001: Amendments to ISPM 5: Glossary of phytosanitary terms - 2006-004: International movement of used vehicles, machinery and equipment - 2009-003: International movement of seeds - 2004-009: Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Erwinia amylovora (Burrill) - 2004-015: Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Genus Anastrepha - 2004-017: Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Ditylenchus dipsaci and Ditylenchus destructor - 2004-018: Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Phytoplasmas - 2009-105: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - High temperature forced air treatment for Bactrocera melanotus and B. xanthodes (Diptera: Tephritidae) on Carica papaya - 2009-109: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Vapour heat treatment for Bactrocera dorsalis on Carica papaya var. Solo - 2010-102: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Cold treatment for Ceratitis capitata on Citrus clementina var. Clemenules - 2010-103: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Cold treatment for Ceratitis capitata on Citrus sinensis var. Navel and Valencia - 2010-106: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Vapour heat treatment for Ceratitis capitata on Mangifera indica - 2012-009: Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Irradiation for Ostrinia nubilalis **The 2014 member consultation (MC) period will last 150 days, from 1st July to 30th November 2014.** **Presentations for the draft standards were posted below on 23 June 2014 for use at IPPC regional workshops and as needed for member consultation.** **The mechanism to translate Diagnostic Protocols into languages before member consultation can be found [here](/node/503).** In 2015, two member consultation periods will be held for Diagnostic Protocols (DPs), as per CPM-9 (2014) Report, paragraph 33: \"The Secretariat informed CPM that due to the high volume of diagnostic protocols that are foreseen to be finalized for member consultation in the coming few years, two member consultation periods for diagnostic protocols will be held in 2015, with the additional period starting on 1 February 2015 and the regular member consultation starting 1 July 2015.\" Please note that previous versions of draft ISPMs going through member consultation and their background documents are available in the [MC archive page](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/mc-draft-ispms-archive). <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-09-01 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','462'),(377,'The IPPC Secretariat posts below all the compiled comments on draft ISPMs from the <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms\">2013 Member Consultation period</a>. Comments were submitted through the IPPC Official Contact Point between 1 July 2013 and 1 December 2013. <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms\">The draft ISPMs approved for member consultation by the Standards Committee in May 2013</a> were: - 1994-001: Draft amendments to ISPM 5: Glossary of phytosanitary terms - 2005-004: Movement of growing media in association with plants for planting in international trade - 2005-010: Phytosanitary procedures for Fruit Fly (Tephritidae) management - 2006-029: Management of pest risks associated with the international movement of wood - 2008-001: Minimizing pest movement by sea containers ** - 2004-011: Draft Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri - 2006-022: Draft Annex to ISPM 27:2006 - Potato spindle tuber viroid - 2012-011: Draft Annex to ISPM 28:2007 - Irradiation for mealybugs ** A preliminary draft as revised during the SC 2013 May meeting was approved for member consultation (with the understanding that there will be a further member consultation), the draft would be open only for general conceptual comments. The IPPC Secretariat requests members to review the compiled comments and <a href=\"mailto:ippc@fao.org\">contact the Secretariat</a> if their comments have not been recorded correctly. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-12-03 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p> ','469'),(378,'At CPM-5 (2010), the Secretariat introduced a paper describing how the diagnostic protocols (DPs) are developed by an international group of experts. Most of the work is done in English and most of the reference documents are in English, and translating the DPs before adoption has a great cost. The proposal was to develop these DPs in English and translate into languages after adoption. Some members, although they empathized with non-English speakers, supported the development of DPs in English to save time and financial resources. However, some other members, while understanding the reasons for the proposal, suggested that the translation should continue to ensure that all technical experts have access to the DPs. The CPM agreed that DPs be translated at two stages: before member consultation, upon request by an IPPC member, for translation into official FAO languages; and as normal, prior to the adoption of the DP by CPM. The CPM requested the Secretariat to provide a mechanism for requests for translation of DPs into FAO languages before member consultation (available below). <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-19 by Adriana Moreira. If you have any question, please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:adriana.moreira@fao.org\">adriana.moreira@fao.org.</a><br></p>','503'),(379,'','26430'),(380,'Draft ISPMs submitted for adoption by the <a href=\"/core-activities/governance/cpm\">Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM)</a> are posted on the <a href=\"/core-activities/governance/cpm\">CPM page</a> in languages at least six weeks prior to the opening of the CPM meeting. In accordance with the IPPC Standard Setting Procedure adopted by CPM-7 (2012), members may submit Formal Objections on draft ISPMs to the IPPC Secretariat at least 14 days before the CPM. All draft ISPMs presented to the CPM are subject to a formal objection. If a CPM member has a formal objection, the member submits the formal objection along with the technical justification and suggestions for improvement of the draft ISPM to the Secretariat no later than 14 days prior to the CPM meeting and the draft ISPM should be returned to the SC. If no formal objection is received, the CPM should adopt the ISPM without discussion. In exceptional circumstances, not including diagnostic protocols and phytosanitary treatments, there should be an opportunity for the CPM Chair, in consultation with the SC Chair and the Secretariat, to propose a discussion of a formal objection at CPM with the aim that the formal objection can be lifted and the ISPM be adopted. A formal objection should be a technically supported objection to the adoption of the draft standard in its current form, sent through the official IPPC contact point. The Secretariat would not make any judgement about the validity of the objection &ndash; an objection with some technical discussion of the issue would be accepted as a formal objection. The Secretariat makes available all formal objections at the start of the CPM. Formal objections for draft ISPMs presented to CPM-9 (2014) must be submitted to the IPPC Secretariat (<a href=\"mailto:ippc@fao.org\">ippc@fao.org</a>) no later than 17 March 2014. For any questions or concerns, please contact the IPPC Secretariat (<a href=\"mailto:ippc@fao.org\">ippc@fao.org</a>). <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-19 by Brent Larson. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:brent.larson@fao.org\">brent.larson@fao.org.</a><br></p>','471'),(381,'Taking into account the <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/compiled-member-comments-draft-standards\">comments received during the 150 day member consultation</a>, the Standards Committee Working Group (SC-7) or Technical Panel (TP) (for diagnostic protocols, phytosanitary treatments and amendments to the glossary) revise the draft ISPM. Once the SC-7 or TP recommends the draft ISPM to the SC, the Secretariat posts the draft ISPM in the IPPC Online Comment System (<a href=\"http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html#\">OCS</a>) and opens the draft for the substantial concerns commenting period. All substantial concerns must be submitted by the IPPC contact point in the IPPC Online Comment System (<a href=\"http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html#\">OCS</a>). For more information on the OCS, please visit the <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/ippc-online-comment-system\">OCS page on the IPP</a>). Please contact the IPPC Secretariat for assistance using the OCS: <IPPC-OCS@fao.org>. The draft ISPMs are only accessible to IPPC official contact points and invited assistants and reviewers and they can be downloaded from the <a href=\"http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html#\">OCS</a>. The SC-7 in May 2014 has submitted the following draft ISPMs for the Substantial Concerns Commenting Period (SCCP): ?	1994-001: Draft Amendments to ISPM 5 (Glossary of phytosanitary terms) ?	2005-004: International movement of growing media in association with plants for planting ?	2005-010: Phytosanitary procedures for Fruit Fly (Tephritidae) management ?	2006-029: International movement of wood **The 2014 substantial concerns commenting period will last 120 days, from 1 June 2014 to 30 September 2014.** <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-05-27 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','519'),(382,'The following draft ISPMs were submitted for Substantial Concerns Commenting Period by the SC-7 in May 2013: - 2006-003: Appendix to ISPM 12 on Electronic certification, information on standard XML schemes and exchange mechanisms - 2009-007: Establishment of fruit fly quarantine areas within a pest free area in the event of an outbreak - 2006-031: Determination of host status of fruits and vegetables to fruit fly (Tephritidae) infestation The Secretariat will post all substantial concerns received before the close of the commenting period below. The SC members review comments submitted from their region and forward those comments deemed to be most important to the steward(s), accompanied by suggestions on how to address them. The steward(s) or relevant TP reviews the comments, prepares responses to the comments and revises the draft ISPM and submits them to the Secretariat. These are posted for the SC. The SC reviews the substantial comments submitted, the Steward(s)&rsquo; responses to the comments and the revised ISPM. The SC provides a summary of the major issues discussed by the SC for each draft ISPM which are recorded in the report of the SC meeting. The SC decides whether to recommend the draft ISPM to the CPM, or to put it on hold, return it to the Steward(s) or to an expert drafting group, or submit it for another round of member consultation. The Secretariat posts the draft ISPM on the IPP in the languages of the organization as soon as possible and at least 6 weeks prior to the opening of the CPM meeting. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-10-01 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','520'),(383,'','26431'),(384,'<p class=\"warning floatcenter\">LATEST NEWS!</a><br></p> **The Notification period for the draft diagnostic protocols DPs, *Phyllosticta citricarpa* (McAlpine) Aa on fruit (2004-023) and *Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri* (2004-011) is started today 01 July 2014 and it will close on 15 August 2014**. The SC approved, via e-decision, to submit the following draft DPs to the 45-days notification period starting in 01 July 2014: - *Phyllosticta citricarpa* (McAlpine) Aa on fruit (2004-023) - *Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri* (2004-011). ----------- According to the stage 4 of the Standard Setting process, **adoption and publication**, all draft ISPMs presented to the CPM are subject to a [formal objection](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/formal-objections-draft-ispms-14-days-prior-cpm). If a contracting party (CP) has a formal objection, the CP submits the formal objection along with the technical justification and suggestions for improvement of the draft ISPM to the Secretariat. **For Diagnostic Protocols (DPs)**, the CPM has delegated its authority to adopt DPs on its behalf to the Standards Committee (SC). This reflects the decision number 8 on the new Standard Setting process by [CPM-7 (2012)](https://www.ippc.int/publications/cpm-7-report-2012-1). Once the Standards Committee approves the DP, the Secretariat makes it available and Contracting Parties are notified*. **The notification period for approved DPs is twice a year on the following defined dates:** **- From 01 July to 15 August** **- From 15 December to 30 January** **Contracting Parties have 45 days to review the approved DP and submit a formal objection, if any.** If no formal objection is received, the SC, on behalf of the CPM, adopts the DP. DPs adopted through this process are noted by the CPM and attached to the report of the CPM meeting. A formal objection should be a technically supported objection to the adoption of the approved diagnostic protocol in its current form, sent through the official IPPC contact point. The Secretariat would not make any judgement about the validity of the objection ? an objection with some technical discussion of the issue would be accepted as a formal objection. The Secretariat will make available all formal objections received. Formal objections for approved diagnostic protocols must be submitted to the IPPC Secretariat via email at <IPPC@fao.org>. For any questions or concerns, please contact the IPPC Secretariat (<IPPC@fao.org>). ________________________ *For translation of Diagnostic Protocols (DPs), members would follow the mechanism for requesting the translation for DPs into FAO languages posted on the IPP by [clicking here](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-ispms/mechanism-translate-diagnostic-protocols-languages). <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-06-25 by Adriana Moreira. For further information please e-mail her at <a href=\"mailto:adriana.moreira@fao.org\">adriana.moreira@fao.org</a><br></p> ','27202'),(385,'This is the master page for Draft specifications. It includes three subpages: - [Member consultation on draft specifications for ISPMs](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-specifications-ispms \"Member consultation on draft specifications for ISPMs\") - [Archive](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-specifications-ispms/archive \"Archive\") - [Compiled member comments on draft specifications](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/compiled-member-comments-draft-specifications \"Compiled member comments on draft specifications\") <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-24 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','15331'),(386,'The Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM) approves new topics for International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPM). The Standards Committee (SC) assigns a steward to each topic who, in consultation with the IPPC Secretariat, drafts a specification. Specifications for ISPMs outline the content and scope of a future ISPM and provide the expert drafting group (EDG) on what to consider while drafting the ISPM. Comments are submitted through the IPPC contact point in the IPPC Online Comment System (OCS, [ocs.ippc.int/index.html](http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html)). For more information on the OCS, please visit the [OCS page on the IPP](/node/504). Please contact the IPPC Secretariat (<IPPC-OCS@fao.org>) for assistance using the OCS. The next consultation period will last 60 days: [from 20 December 2014 to 20 February 2015](http://ocs.ippc.int/index.html). **Please note that previous versions of draft specifications going through member consultation and their background documents are available in the [MC on draft specifications archive page](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/member-consultation-draft-specifications-ispms/archive).** <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-06-23 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','455'),(387,'','26432'),(388,'Draft specifications are reviewed by the Standards Committee and, once approved for member consultation, are then made available on the IPP for a 60 day member consultation period. Comments received by the IPPC Secretariat are compiled, posted on the IPP and submitted to the steward(s) and Standards Committee for consideration. The specification is amended as necessary, finalized and approved by the Standards Committee, and published on the [IPP](http://www.ippc.int \"IPP\"). The IPPC Secretariat will post below all the compiled comments on draft specifications from the <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/index.php%3Fid%3D190935\">second 2013 Member Consultation period</a>. All comments were submitted through the IPPC Official Contact Point between 20 December 2013 and 20 February 2014. <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/index.php%3Fid%3D190935\">The draft specifications approved for member consultation by the Standards Committee in November 2013</a> were: - Revision of ISPM 6:1997 - Guidelines for surveillance (2009-004) - International movement of grain (2008-007) The IPPC Secretariat requests members to review the compiled comments and <a href=\"mailto:ippc@fao.org\">contact the Secretariat</a> if their comments have not been recorded correctly. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2014-02-21 by Mirko Montuori. If you find any incorrect information, please e-mail him at <a href=\"mailto:mirko.montuori@fao.org\">mirko.montuori@fao.org.</a><br></p>','488'),(389,'','27496'),(390,'<p>This page includes three subpages: [Calls for topics](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/calls-topics &quot;Calls for topics&quot;), [Calls for experts](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/calls-experts &quot;Calls for experts&quot;), and [Calls for treatments](https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/calls-treatments &quot;Calls for treatments&quot;). Click on the relevant subpage link above or on the right hand menu to check the one you are interested in. All closed calls are kept under the archive pages.</p><p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-06-24. For further information, please contact <a href=\"mailto:nuri.niyazi@fao.org\">nuri.niyazi@fao.org</a>.</p>','15334'),(391,'The IPPC Secretariat makes a call for topics every two years. IPPC members and <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels\">Technical Panels (TPs)</a> submit detailed proposals for new topics or for the revision of existing ISPMs to the IPPC Secretariat. Submissions should be accompanied with a draft specification, a literature review and justification that the proposed topic meets the CPM-approved criteria for topics (available in the <a href=\"/core-activities/governance/ippc-procedure-manual\">IPPC Procedure Manual</a>). To indicate a broader need for the proposed topic, submitters are encouraged to gain support from other IPPC members and/or regions. The IPPC Secretariat compiles a list of the proposed topics from the submissions received. Submissions from previous years are not included, but IPPC members may re-submit these, as appropriate. The Standards Committee (SC), taking into account the IPPC Strategic Framework and the Criteria for justification and prioritization of proposed topics, reviews the existing List of topics for IPPC standards and the compiled list of proposed topics. The SC recommends a revised List of topics for IPPC standards (including subjects), adding topics from the compiled list, deleting or modifying topics in the existing List of topics for IPPC standards as appropriate, giving each topic a recommended priority. The CPM reviews the List of topics for IPPC standards recommended by the SC. The CPM adjusts and adopts the List of topics for IPPC standards, including assigning a priority for each topic. A revised List of topics for IPPC standards is made available. In any year, when a situation arises in which an ISPM is required urgently, the CPM may insert such a topic into the List of topics for IPPC standards. <p class=\"warning floatcenter\">2013 Call for Topics</a><br></p> **Thank you to all IPPC members and TPs who submitted proposals to the 2013 Call for Topics. The proposed topics will follow the process as mentioned above.** The compiled submissions is posted below. *This web page was last updated on 2013-12-05 by Adriana Moreira. For further information, please e-mail her at <adriana.moreira@fao.org>.*','15335'),(392,'[Please see here](/core-activities/calls-topics)','15338'),(393,'','26369'),(394,'<p>As decided by ICPM-7 (2005), a call for work programme topics is made every two years. Detailed proposals for new topics or for the revision of existing ISPMs are submitted to the IPPC Secretariat.</p>','442'),(395,'The IPPC Secretariat makes a call for topics every two years. IPPC members and <a href=\"/core-activities/standards-setting/expert-drafting-groups/technical-panels\">Technical Panels (TPs)</a> submit detailed proposals for new topics or for the revision of existing ISPMs to the IPPC Secretariat. Submissions should be accompanied with a draft specification, a literature review and justification that the proposed topic meets the CPM-approved criteria for topics (available in the <a href=\"/core-activities/governance/ippc-procedure-manual\">IPPC Procedure Manual</a>). To indicate a broader need for the proposed topic, submitters are encouraged to gain support from other IPPC members and/or regions. Topics being solicited include the following: - new topics for International Standards for Phytosanitary Measures (ISPMs) - new components to existing ISPMs, such as supplements, annexes or appendices - revisions or amendments to adopted ISPMs, supplements, annexes, appendices or glossary terms - pests for which a new diagnostic protocol should be developed - new topics for phytosanitary treatments. Note that specific treatment submission data will be called for at a later date. **Documents to the 2013 Call for Topics** *The following documents are posted bellow* - Call for Topics Letter (English, Espa?ol, Fran?ais) - Submission form for IPPC standard setting work programme topics - 2013 (English, Espa?ol, Fran?ais) (Note: Posted on 2013-05-20) - Procedures for identifying topics and priorities for standards (English, Espa?ol, Fran?ais) - List of Topics for IPPC Standards. [click here to access](https://www.ippc.int/publications/list-topics-ippc-standards) **All documents must be submitted by the National IPPC Official Contact Point, preferably in electronic format to <IPPC@fao.org>, no later than 31 August 2013 (title message: \"Call for Topics - 2013\").** *This web page was last updated on 2013-08-22 by Adriana Moreira. For further information, please e-mail her at <adriana.moreira@fao.org>.*','26858'),(396,'<p>Once the Standards Committee (SC) approves a specification and resources are identified to hold an expert working group (EWG) meeting, the IPPC Secretariat contacts NPPOs and RPPOs through a **call to nominate experts** to be members of the EWG to develop a draft ISPM. In order to get nominated as an expert the nominee is requested to sign a statement of commitment. The SC selects the technical experts identified by the NPPOs and RPPOs for the EWG. The EWG meets and produces a draft ISPM and a meeting report. The draft ISPM is then approved for member consultation by the SC. Members of Technical Panels (TPs) should have the necessary scientific expertise and subject matter experience, and should be able to participate and contribute to the proceedings. The steward of the TP is considered a member. Membership of TPs should be reviewed by the SC on a regular basis and may be adjusted as necessary, taking into account, in particular, changes in the needs of scientific or other expertise required and in the professional duties of the experts. Currently, there is no Call for experts open.</p><p class=\"warning floatcenter\">This web page was last updated on 2013-11-29. For more information, please contact&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:nuri.niyazi@fao.org\">nuri.niyazi@fao.org</a>.</p>','15336'),(397,'<p><strong>2013 December - Expert Consultation on Cold Treatments (ECCT) Buenos Aires, Argentina</strong>.</p><p>The International Plant Protection Convention (IPPC) Secretariat is soliciting nominations for qualified experts and scientists to participate in the Expert Consultation on Cold Treatments to identify collect and evaluate information on existing cold treatments that are needed for regulated pests and regulated articles and that may be implemented at a global level. Selected experts are also welcome to present any approved new schedules for use at an international level between contracting parties and for building confidence in cold treatments as a phytosanitary measure. Nominations were due 30 August 2013. Please note that experts are selected and this call is closed.</p><p><strong>Specific requirements</strong></p><p><strong><em>1. The expertise required for participation in the ECCT is in accordance with the meeting programme (see provisional programme).</em></strong></p><p>&nbsp;- The experts confirmed should be available to attend the meeting of the ECCT on 02-06 December 2013. These dates can be found on the IPPC Calendar. - Interested persons/parties should send an email to the IPPC Secretariat (ippc@fao.org) no later than 30 August 2013. The email should provide an abstract of the proposed presentation (500 words maximum) in accordance with the provisional programme as well as a brief CV providing qualifications to speak on the topic. - Nominations are being solicited by the Steering Committee of the ECCT and the Secretariat of the International Plant Protection Convention (IPPC) for speakers to address the ECCT as a phytosanitary measure to control regulated pests. - Criteria for selection of participants: - Area of expertise (industry, science, regulation etc.) - Experience - Current research or work on cold treatments - Future research or work - List of papers on cold treatments - Relevance of the papers - Geographical representation - Representation from developing countries - English language skills - Abstract of proposed presentation 400-500 words maximum - All materials will be posted on the IPPC website. NOTE: Only a limited number of speakers will be selected to address the ECCT.</p><p><strong><em>2. Funding</em></strong></p><p>- Participants are encouraged to have their travel expenses covered by their respective countries. - A limited number of experts from developing countries will be funded according to the IPPC criteria for prioritizing participants to receive travel assistance. - Countries or organizations which are interested in translation of the meeting into their languages should send the proposals for funding to the IPPC Secretariat.</p>','20838'),(398,'','26439'),(399,'<p>The deadline for receipt of nominations was 10 April 2010.</p>','491'),(400,'<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\"> <p class=\"Default\" style=\"margin: 0cm 34.85pt 0pt 1cm; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\">The International Plant Protection Convention (IPPC) Secretariat is soliciting nominations for appropriately qualified experts to take part in the Technical panel for phytosanitary treatments (TPPT) and the Technical panel for the glossary (TPG). Nominations are due <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">31 August 2012</strong>. </span></p> <p class=\"Default\" style=\"margin: 0cm 34.85pt 0pt 1cm; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\">&nbsp;</span></p> <p class=\"Default\" style=\"margin: 0cm 34.85pt 0pt 1cm; text-align: justify; mso-outline-level: 1;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\">Specific expertise required</span></span></strong></p> <p class=\"Default\" style=\"margin: 0cm 34.85pt 0pt 1cm; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \" lang=\"EN-CA\">&nbsp;</span></p> <p class=\"Default\" style=\"margin: 0cm 34.85pt 0pt 1cm; text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 