ame=\"Medium Grid 1 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"68\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 2 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"69\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Medium Grid 3 Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"70\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Dark List Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"71\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Shading Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"72\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful List Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"73\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" Name=\"Colorful Grid Accent 6\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"19\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Emphasis\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"21\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Emphasis\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"31\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Subtle Reference\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"32\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Intense Reference\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"33\" SemiHidden=\"false\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\"false\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"Book Title\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"37\" Name=\"Bibliography\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\"false\" Priority=\"39\" QFormat=\"true\" Name=\"TOC Heading\" /> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\r\n<style>  /* Style Definitions */  table.MsoNormalTable 	{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\"; 	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; 	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; 	mso-style-noshow:yes; 	mso-style-priority:99; 	mso-style-qformat:yes; 	mso-style-parent:\"\"; 	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; 	mso-para-margin-top:0cm; 	mso-para-margin-right:0cm; 	mso-para-margin-bottom:10.0pt; 	mso-para-margin-left:0cm; 	line-height:115%; 	mso-pagination:widow-orphan; 	font-size:11.0pt; 	font-family:\"Times New Roman\",\"serif\";} </style>\r\n<![endif]-->for electronic phytosanitary certification - ePhyto;</li>\r\n<li>used reduction of potential of fraudulent documentation;</li>\r\n<li>reduce data entry and validation functions by NPPO&rsquo;S staff i.e gains in efficiency;</li>\r\n<li>improve security in transmission of certificate documentation (electronic versus paper);</li>\r\n<li>improve planning for the arrival and clearance of plants and plant products at customs that will need phytosanitary clearance ;</li>\r\n<li>reduction in delays in receiving replacement Phyto-sanitary (SPS) certificates;</li>\r\n<li>maximize the investment by building on initiatives already in place;</li>\r\n<li>substantially reduce the need for ongoing and costly bilateral discussions on electronic phytosanitary standards;</li>\r\n<li>ability to link into the World Customs Organization \"One Window\" initiative and harmonize codes and processes; and</li>\r\n<li>employ international e-business standards between governments (UN/CEFACT).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The meeting is open to everyone &mdash; register with <a href=\"file_uploaded/1351698417_REGISTRATION-FORM-brazil-ephyto-.doc\">this form</a> &mdash; but will have to be limited to about 100 participants. Funding  support for travel and accomodation for developing countries is very  limited and will be available for national support only.</p>\r\n<p>Registration and the opening ceremony will take place on Monday 19 November 2012.</p>','522'),(448,'The IPPC ePhyto Steering Group was established by the 8th session of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM) to commence work on key components to assist countries with their implementation of ePhyto.\r\n\r\nCPM-8 (2013) recognized the need for a programme to specifically promote and provide guidance on the development of ePhyto, and provide information and tools for those countries that opt to use an ePhyto system.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of the ePhyto Steering Group is to provide oversight, guidance and advice on IPPC efforts to facilitate the international exchange of electronic phytosanitary information among contracting parties.\r\n\r\nBelow you can find some of the awareness material developed by the ePhyto Steering Group.','27292'),(449,'\r\nUnder the IPPC, information exchange is the responsibility of member countries  [National Plant Protection Organizations][1] (NPPOs), the [IPPC Secretariat][2] and [Regional Plant Protection Organizations][3] (RPPOs).\r\nEach member country should identify a contact point for all IPPC matters, provide a description of the NPPO, list points of entry under official control, list regulated pests, notify changes to its pest status, phytosanitary measures, regulations, and other relevant information.\r\nDepending on circumstances, these notifications should be provided to other countries, to RPPOs and to the Secretariat through the IPPC website. For more information about reporting, see the [Convention][4] and the reports of the sessions of the [Commission&nbsp;on Phytosanitary Measures][5]\r\nSharing information about your pest status, phytosanitary measures, regulations and other information is vital to the future of the world^s plant resources and biodiversity, to safe trade in plants and plant products, and to food security.\r\nSharing information on regulations, pest outbreaks, control, surveillance and treatments builds cooperation and enhances member countries^ capacity to protect their plant resources. Countries use this information to assess the risks associated with moving plants and plant products across borders, and to manage those risks wisely.\r\n\r\nInformation exchange supports transparency and risk analysis by:\r\n\r\n- promoting the control of pests and preventing their spread\r\n- sharing technical information on which to base decisions\r\n- using international standards\r\n- promoting the harmonization of phytosanitary measures; and\r\n- meeting the public information requirements of the Convention.\r\n\r\nThe Secretariat uses the information provided by member countries to coordinate the IPPC work programme, to review the state of plant protection around the world, to help in dispute avoidance and to inform CPM decisions. The Secretariat does this by:\r\n\r\n- providing translation and documentation services for IPPC-related activities\r\n- distributing IPPC and related documentation, such as ISPMs\r\n- managing the IPPC Web site to communicate the Secretariat activities, to highlight RPPO and NPPO activities, to publish documentation relating to the IPPC, and to provide technical information on phytosanitary measures\r\n- providing the forum for countries to develop and agree to ISPMs\r\n- developing the network of IPPC contact points to provide fast, reliable exchange between member countries, and between member countries, the Secretariat and RPPOs\r\n- informing member countries of meetings organized by the IPPC Secretariat and by RPPOs\r\n- providing a global pest reporting system\r\n- encouraging and emphasizing technical assistance on phytosanitary measures and providing technical assistance from the FAO\r\n- organizing technical meetings to discuss emerging issues, to draft international standards or to clarify specific phytosanitary concerns\r\n- providing training.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /countries\r\n  [2]: /core-activities/governance/the-secretariat-of-the-ippc\r\n  [3]: /rppos\r\n  [4]: /node/9279\r\n  [5]: /core-activities/governance/cpm','433'),(450,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n\r\nThe IPP Support Group is an advisory body to the IPPC Secretariat made up of contracting party nominated experts in the area of information exchange under the IPPC. This group met annually from 2004 through 2006 to review progress with the IPP and provide advice on future developments.\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/coreactivities_pages/1158046438881_ipp_support_group_wageningen_sept05_08_2006_01.jpg','441'),(451,'Between 2005 and 2008, the IPPC Secretariat arranged regional workshops to explain national phytosanitary information exchange obligations, and to train official contact points and nominated information officers in using the IPPC website to meet these obligations. \r\n\r\nAt present, training and capacity development is being undertaken nationally or sub-regionally. Training events are often held in conjunction with other IPPC activities.','473'),(452,'FAO held a sub-regional workshop (financed by TCP/for the Central African Countries to discuss information exchange and communication within the framework of the IPPC. This workshop was held from 01-03 November 2012.\r\n\r\nAll materials for the Central African workshop on IPPC national reporting obligations.','527'),(453,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n\r\nAn APPPC training workshop for \"Capacity Building in the Use of the Interntional Phytosanitary Portal (IPP) and APPPC Website for Information Exchange\".\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/coreactivities_pages/9909fee0f1.jpg','505'),(454,'FAO held a second sub-regional workshop (financed by TCP/for the Central African Countries) to discuss national reporting obligations within the framework of the IPPC - the focus this time was on the national editors. This workshop was held from 25-29 June 2013 In Libreville, Gabon.\r\n\r\nAll materials for the Central African workshop on IPPC national reporting obligations can be found below.','26463'),(455,'One of the requirements of the CPM is to maintain an overview of the state of plant protection in the world. An important aspect of this is the need to be aware of, and ready to react to, any new or emerging issues and/or incorporate new technologies.','459'),(456,'**Workshop on Invasive Alien Species and the IPPCBraunschweig, Germany, 22-26 September 2003**\r\n![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\nThe workshop was set up to help phytosanitary experts, environmentalists, and regulators exchange ideas and learn how the IPPC and related tools may help in the management of invasive alien species. The programme addressed some of the most topical issues that are confronting both phytosanitary services and environmental protection agencies with regard to invasive alien species. The workshop was attended by over 100 participants representing 60 countries. \r\n\r\n[see more...][2]</link>\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/coreactivities_pages/1259315411_ias_breakout_groups.jpg\r\n  [2]: http://www.fao.org/documents/show_cdr.asp?url_file=/docrep/008/y5968e/y5968e00.htm','440'),(457,'.','456'),(458,'The IPPC Secretariat is collecting background information on the implementation of Pest Free Areas (PFAs) in countries as requested by CPM 1. This survey has been sent to national IPPC contact points and they have been requested to <b>complete this survey on-line by 30 November 2006 (deadline has been extended)</b>. The listed documents provide copies of the letters sent to the IPPC contact points, and provides a paper version of the survey to faciltate data collection before the survey is completed on-line.','448'),(459,'<p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The <a href=\"http://irss.ippc.int\">Implementation Review and Support System (IRSS)</a> has as its primary objective the facilitation and promotion of the implementation of the IPPC and ISPMs. Advantages of the IRSS include: the ability to monitor, encourage and support the harmonised implementation of the IPPC and its ISPMs by contracting parties; and a means to identify and address emerging and potential implementation problems before they became disputes, through an assistance-based and non-confrontational process.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">There are three primary components of the IRSS:</p>\r\n<ol class=\"ol1\">\r\n<li class=\"li2\">Implementation review system - monitors of the fulfillment of reporting requirements and other obligations under the IPPC as well as the implementation of standards.</li>\r\n<li class=\"li2\">Implementation support system - consists of an active &ldquo;standard implementation support programme&rdquo; in the form of a help desk available to all contracting parties.</li>\r\n<li class=\"li2\">Implementation review response - summarizes the situation of the implementation of the IPPC and its standards by contracting parties. From this summary, action plans are developed, for input into the proposed work programme for consideration by the CPM. The recommended action plans are a key input into the strategic and technical assistance planning of the CPM.</li>\r\n</ol></p>','460'),(460,'<p><strong>Dear IPPC Contact Points</strong>,</p>\r\n<p>In an effort to catalogue the gaps and challenges faced by NPPO&rsquo;s for the implementation of ISPM 8, the IRSS team invites you to complete the following mini-questionnaire. The results of this exercise will be used to make recommendations to the review panel for this standard on ways to improve it in the upcoming revision of the standard.</p>\r\n<p>The results of the ISPM&nbsp;8 mini-questionnaire will also be used as a basis for a brief side-discussion at the end of the upcoming ISPM6 regional workshops: <a href=\"/node/506\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Global review of phytosanitary surveillance in the context of ISPM6</span></strong></a></p>\r\n<p><strong>We kindly urge you to complete the ISPM8 mini-questionnaire by December 31, 2011</strong>. You must be logged on to your IPP account to access and download the questionnaire.</p>\r\n<p>If you are unable to use or access the online survey, please enter your responses using the Microsoft Word 2003 document provided.&nbsp; Please enter you response in your language along with a rough translation in English. Return the completed survey in word 2003 format to: <a href=\"mailto:ippc@fao.org\">ippc@fao.org</a> with the subject line: [your country name] <strong>IRSS ISPM8 Response</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Due to limited resources we apologize that this survey will not be available in other languages.</p>\r\n<p>We invite you to participate fully in this activity and thank you in advance for your collaboration.</p>\r\n<p>The IPPC IRSS Team</p>','508'),(461,'<p>A foundation activity of NPPOs is the conduct of pest surveillance. The products of pest surveillance provide the basis for pest listing, identification of pest status, pest reporting, pest categorization and the conduct of pest risk analyses.</p>\r\n<p>In 2004, the IPPC approved ISPM6: Guidelines for surveillance as a basis to assist NPPOs for implementing this fundamental activity. In 2011, ISPM6 was flagged for review by the Standards Committee of the IPPC. The newly initiated Implementation Review and Support System (IRSS) of the IPPC, will play a role in the review of the standard. The IRSS is an overarching programme of the IPPC aimed at identifying challenges of contracting parties for implementation of the IPPC and its standards as well as identifying resources for resolving those challenges.</p>\r\n<p>The IRSS is launching a series of workshops in several regions of the world to catalogue the challenges faced by NPPOs for the implementation of ISPM6 with a view to making recommendations to the review panel of the ISPM6 on ways to improve it. The IRSS will also be gathering examples of best practice globally so that appropriate training material and manuals might be prepared under the capacity development programme of the IPPC. The APPPC has been identified as a partner in this endeavour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The primary objective of this series of workshops is to identify concrete ways to improve the implementation of ISPM6.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','506'),(462,'<p><strong>Dear IPPC Contact Points,</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Subsidiary Body on Dispute Settlement (SBDS) has initiated a review of its role and functions. The review will consider processes to address issues related to implementation of ISPMs that do not amount to a formal dispute. The SBDS expects to present recommendations on its role, scope and functions to CPM-8.</p>\r\n<p>To facilitate the review the SBDS required information on the implementation of ISPM13 (guidelines for the notification of non-compliances and emergency action) and a better understanding of the precursors to possible disputes and dispute settlement actions by contracting parties.</p>\r\n<p>As a way to assist in conducting this review you are invited to complete this 6 part questionnaire.</p>\r\n<p>We kindly urge you to complete the ISPM13 Questionnaire which can be downloaded below, by<strong> the extended date of December 31, 2012.</strong></p>\r\n<p>You can also complete the ISPM13 Questionnaire on-line here<strong>:</strong>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/ISPM13review\"><strong>https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/ISPM13review</strong></a></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>Return the completed questionnaire to <strong>Nadia.Villasenor@fao.org and ippc@fao.org</strong> with the subject line: <strong>IRSS ISPM13 response [your country name].</strong></p>\r\n<p>We thank you for your collaboration.</p>\r\n<p>The IRSS Team</p>','509'),(463,'This open-ended working group was held to review mechanisms used by other organizations and to explore the possibilities of such a potential compliance mechanism under the IPPC. Approximately 30 delegates and resource people took part in the OEWG.\r\n\r\nThe OEWG developed the IPPC- Implementation Review and Support System(IRSS), which built on existing, or planned, processes already approved by the CPM, with the primary objective of facilitating and promoting the implementation of the IPPC and ISPMs.','452'),(465,'<p><u>Partnerships</u> can range from informal, flexible arrangements to highly defined relationships <em>based on the full sharing of risks, resources and responsibilities</em>.</p><p>The IPPC recognises the importance of maintaining strong links with international organizations that share common interests, in particular the <a href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations\">Regional Plant Protection Organizations</a> and <a href=\"/partners/international-organizations\">International Organizations</a> such as the <a href=\"partners/international-organizations/convention-biological-diversity\">Convention on Biological Diversity</a>.</p><p>The IPPC cooperates with Regional Plant Protection Organizations in achieving the objectives of the Convention and their role is articulated in the Convention.</p>','5'),(466,'<p> <p>In order to achieve&nbsp;its&nbsp;mission, the IPPC recognises the importance of maintaining strong links with international organizations that share common interests.</p> <p>The IPPC liaises with relevant international organizations who assist with capacity building both regionally and nationally as well as participate in some meetings as observers.</p> </p> <p>Partner organizations are:</p> <ul> <li><a href=\"/partners/international-organizations/convention-biological-diversity\">Convention on Biological Diversity</a></li> <li><a href=\"/partners/international-organizations/codex-alimentarius\">Codex Alimentarius</a></li> </ul> <p>&nbsp;</p>','8101'),(485,'<p><span lang=\"EN\"> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"bodytext\"><span lang=\"EN\">A Regional Plant Protection Organization (RPPO) is an inter-governmental organization functioning as a coordinating body for National Plant Protection Organizations (NPPO) on a regional level. Not all contracting parties to the IPPC are members of RPPOs, nor are all members of RPPOs contracting parties to the IPPC. Moreover, certain contracting parties to the IPPC belong to more than one RPPO. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"bodytext\"><span lang=\"EN\">There are currently 10 RPPOs:</span></p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/asia-pacific-plant-protection-commission\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Asia and Pacific Plant Protection Commission (APPPC)</span></strong></a> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/comunidad-andina\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Comunidad Andina (CA)</span></strong></a> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/comite-regional-de-sanidad-vegetal-del-cono-sur-cosave\"><span lang=\"PT-BR\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Comite de Sanidad Vegetal del Cono Sur (COSAVE)</span></strong></span></a></span><span lang=\"PT-BR\"> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/caribbean-plant-protection-commission\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Caribbean Plant Protection Commission (CPPC)</span></strong></a> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/european-mediterranean-plant-protection-organization\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">European and Mediterranean Plant Protection Organization (EPPO)</span></strong></a> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/inter-african-phytosanitary-council\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Inter-African Phytosanitary Council (IAPSC)</span></strong></a></span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\"><a href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/near-east-plant-protection-organization-neppo\">Near East Plant Protection Organization (NEPPO)</a><br /></span></strong></span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/north-american-plant-protection-organization\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">North American Plant Protection Organization (NAPPO)</span></strong></a> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/organismo-internacional-regional-de-sanidad-agropecuaria\"><span lang=\"PT-BR\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Organismo Internacional Regional de Sanidad Agropecuaria (OIRSA)</span></strong></span></a></span><span lang=\"PT-BR\"> </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\"><a class=\"internal-link\" title=\"Opens internal link in current window\" href=\"/partners/regional-plant-protection-organizations/pacific-plant-protection-organisation\"><strong><span style=\"color: #006600;\">Pacific Plant Protection Organization (PPPO)</span></strong></a></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"bodytext\"><span lang=\"EN\">Article IX of the </span>IPPC<span lang=\"EN\"> provides for &nbsp;</span>RPPO contributions to various activities that achieve the objectives of the IPPC<span lang=\"EN\">. It extends the responsibilities of RPPOs to specify cooperation with the </span>IPPC<span lang=\"EN\"> Secretariat and the Commission for Phytosanitary Measures in developing international standards. The RPPOs therefore play an important role in the cooperative endeavour to implement the </span>IPPC<span lang=\"EN\">. </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"bodytext\"><span lang=\"EN\">The functions of RPPOs are mostly laid down in the Article IX of the IPPC&nbsp;and include:</span></p>\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo2; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Coordination and participation in activities among their NPPOs in order to promote and achieve the objectives of the IPPC&nbsp;</span> </li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo2; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Cooperation<span>&nbsp; </span>among regions for promoting harmonized phytosanitary measures </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo2; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Gathering and dissemination of information, in particular in relation with the IPPC&nbsp;</span> </li>\r\n<li style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo2; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;\"><span lang=\"EN\">Cooperation with the CPM and the </span>IPPC<span lang=\"EN\"> Secretariat in developing and implementing international standards for phytosanitary measures.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"bodytext\"><span lang=\"EN\">Each RPPO has its own activities and programme. Each year, a Technical Consultation of representatives of RPPOs and the </span>IPPC<span lang=\"EN\"> Secretariat is convened to encourage inter-regional consultation on harmonized phytosanitary measures for controlling pests and in preventing their spread and/or introduction, and to promote the development and use of relevant ISPMs. To date, there have been 21 Technical Consultations, whose reports are made available on the IPP. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','8074'),(490,'Setting regional standards for phytosanitary measures and plant protection products.\r\n\r\nOrganizing Working Party and Panel meetings bringing together experts from all parts of the EPPO region.\r\n\r\nParticipating in global activities related to phytosanitary measures coordinated by the IPPC Secretariat within FAO.\r\n\r\nOrganizing international conferences and workshops for plant protection researchers, managers of plant protection organizations, phytosanitary inspectors.\r\n\r\nPublishing the journal Bulletin OEPP/EPPO Bulletin, the EPPO Reporting Service and the EPPO Summaries of Phytosanitary Regulations, providing an electronic documentation service, distributing database systems.','8091'),(491,'<p>The EPPO calendar, showing the subjects, dates and places of all EPPO meetings, can be seen by clicking \"See more\".</p> [see more...][1]\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://www.eppo.int/MEETINGS/meetings.htm','8092'),(492,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n<p>EPPO is administered by its Executive Committee (seven Governments elected on a rotational basis, meeting twice a year), under the control of its Council (representatives of all member goverments, meeting once a year) headed by a Chairman and a Vice-Chairman, elected as individuals. The technical work of the Organization is done by the Panels of experts, under the supervision of the Working Parties. Experts are nominated by their National Plant Protection Organizations. A Secretariat (permanent staff of EPPO working at the headquarters in Paris) is headed by a Director-General (Mr R. Arnitis) and Assistant Director (Ms F. Petter)</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/partnerspages/1258031139_48419_1131452315758_eppost.gif','8095'),(493,'EPPT is a database system on the names and classification of more than 50,000 organisms important for plant protection, including scientific names, synonyms, common names, and also EPPO computer codes (formerly Bayer codes). It is freely available on the EPPO website. \r\n\r\n[see more...][1]\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://www.eppo.org/DATABASES/eppt/eppt.htm','8093'),(494,'<p>PQR is the EPPO database on quarantine pests (geographical distribution, host plants, pathways). It can be downloaded free of charge from the EPPO website.</p>\r\n\r\n[see more...][1]\r\n\r\n  [1]: http://%20http://www.eppo.int/DATABASES/pqr/pqr.htm','8094'),(496,'La 23ème Assemblée Générale du CPI-UA est une réunion biennale statutaire du Conseil Phytosanitaire Interafricain qui regroupe les Représentants des Services Nationaux de la Protection des Végétaux. Elle se tiendra cette année au Siège de la Commission de l’Union Africaine à Addis-Abeba en Ethiopie. Cette réunion se déroulera du 26 au 28 mars 2008 juste avant celle de la Commission des Mesures Phytosanitaires (CMP) du 07 au 11 avril 2008 à Rome. Le CPI voudrait inviter le représentant du Service National de la Protection des Végétaux de votre pays à participer à cette Assemblée générale. En outre, l’Assemblée générale 2008 promet d’être un cadre de restructuration et de renouvellement institutionnel du CPI-UA où des issues saillantes sur des stratégies futures du CPI seront discutées. Afin d’encourager la participation, le CPI couvrira les charges (ticket de voyage et perdiem) du premier représentant de chaque pays membre. D’ailleurs, cette participation est d’intérêt particulier pour tous les pays africains parce que des décisions stratégiques sur le CMP à Rome y seront discutées. Tout en espérant que votre présence à cette Assemblée Générale permettra si possible l’apparition des activités complémentaires plus fortes entre le CPI-UA et les Etats membres de l’Union Africaine. Nous vous saurions gré de noter qu’un rapport de pays devra être soumis au CPI-UA et au représentant de la CER dont chaque pays est rattaché. Le vôtre vous contactera personnellement très bientôt. Le Directeur/ Représentant Résident a.i. Dr. Yemi AKINBAMIJO','8111'),(497,'The 23rd General Assembly of the National Representatives of Plant Protection Services is a statutory biennial meeting of the AU-IAPSC, scheduled to hold this year at the African Union Commission Headquarters in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.\r\n\r\nThe meeting has been scheduled for 26-28 March 2008 just ahead of the Committee on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM) Meeting in Rome 7-11 April 2008. In this regard, the IAPSC would like to invite National Plant Protection Services representative of member states to kindly attend the African Union Inter-African Phytosanitary Council General Assembly 2008.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the General Assembly 2008 promises to be a watershed in the institutional renewal and rebirth of the AU-IAPSC where salient issues on future strategies of the IAPSC will be discussed. In order to encourage participation of member states, the IAPSC will cover the cost of participation (travel and per diem) of the first representative of each country. Moreover, it is of particular interest for all African countries representation because strategic decisions on the CPM in Rome will be discussed at the General Assembly. It is hoped that your presence at this General Assembly will allow the emergence of stronger complementary activities between the AU-IAPSC and AU-member states.\r\n\r\nKindly note that a country report is expected to be submitted to AU-IAPSC and to your designated REC representative who shall be contacting you shortly.\r\n\r\nRegards\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYemi  AKINBAMIJO, PhD\r\nAg Director and Head of Mission','8110'),(498,'.','8100'),(499,'<b>Venue</b>:  CAIRO, EGYPT  <br /><br />  <b>Date</b>:  19-24, MARCH 2006','8118'),(501,'<p><strong>President</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp; Dr Mohamed Ali&nbsp; ElHag ALLOBA<br /><br /><strong>Vice President</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp; Dr Hassan Kassem Mohamed BEKHEIT<br /><br /><strong>Governing Council</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp; Consists of all Member States, acts as the supreme body of the Organization. Meet once every two years<br /><br /><strong>Executive Committee</strong>: &nbsp; Six countries elected in principle rotation. Meets at least once a year.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Algeria</li>\r\n<li>Jordan</li>\r\n<li>Libya</li>\r\n<li>Pakistan</li>\r\n<li>Syria</li>\r\n<li>Tunisia</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Executive Director</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp; Dr. Mekki CHOUIBANI</p>','8132'),(502,'<p>NEPPO is hosted by the Kingdom of Morrocco in Rabat:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">c/o ONSSA<br /><br />Avenue Haj Ahmed Cherkaoui. Agdal. Rabat. 10090. Morocco<br /><br />Tel.: +212 673997808, +212 661309104. Fax: +212537682049<br /></p>','8131'),(503,'<p><strong>NEPPO OBJECTIVES</strong><br /><br />The objectives of NEPPO shall be  primarily to promote international cooperation in the region in  strengthening plant protection activities and capabilities with the aim  of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Controlling pests of plants and plant products in an appropriate manner;</li>\r\n<li>Preventing the introduction and spread of pests;</li>\r\n<li>Facilitating safe trade.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','8130'),(507,'<p>Technical Consultations amomg Regional Plant Protection Organizations are regularly convened (annual basis) by the Secretary of the Commission. The prupose of the TC is to inter alia, encourage inter-regional cooperation in promoting harmonized phytosanitary measures, and the development and use of relevant international standards for phytosanitary measures. In addition to being a forum for RPPOs to consult as a group, the TC can support regional programmes under the IPPC and contribute to the work programme of the CPM.</p>\r\n<p>The meeting is open ended and as well as the RPPO Executive Officers, all CPM members are welcome to attend, albeit on a self funding basis.</p>','8098'),(508,'','8133'),(509,'','8128'),(510,'','8097'),(511,'','8099'),(512,'','8112'),(513,'','8115'),(514,'','8125'),(515,'','8078'),(516,'','26696'),(518,'.','8119'),(519,'.','8096'),(530,'<?php global $user; $user = user_load($user->uid); // Work Area for secretariat, country editors and anonymous (not logged-in) users if($user->roles[3] || $user->roles[4]) { // secretariat print t(^ <ul class=\"nobullets\"> <li><a class=\"icn-contact-add\" href=\"/user/^.$GLOBALS[^user^]->uid.^/edit\">Edit Contact & Account Information</a> <span class=\"small quiet\">| <a href=\"/user\">View account information</a> | <a href=\"/user/^.$GLOBALS[^user^]->uid.^/edit#edit-account\">Change password</a></span></li> <!--<li><a class=\"icn-pestreport-add\" href=\"/support/^.$GLOBALS[^user^]->uid.^/assigned\">Support Tickets</a> | <a href=\"/node/add/support-ticket\">add</a></li>--> <li><a class=\"icn-pestreport-add\" href=\"http://it.ippc.int/post/\">Support ticket (IPPC IT Wishlist - it.ippc.int)</a>. <a href=\"http://it.ippc.int/about/\">Read more about the wishlist</a>.</span></li> <li><a class=\"icn-preview\" href=\"/admin/workbench/content/all\">Find Content</a></li> <!--<li><a class=\"bullet-triangle\" href=\"/ext