"[object]\">After registering you will receive a confirmation email containing information about joining the meeting.</p>\r\n<h3 id=\"[object]\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\" title=\"[object]\" lang=\"[object]\" onclick=\"[object]\" ondblclick=\"[object]\" onmousedown=\"[object]\" onmouseup=\"[object]\" onmouseover=\"[object]\" onmousemove=\"[object]\" onmouseout=\"[object]\" onkeypress=\"[object]\" onkeydown=\"[object]\" onkeyup=\"[object]\">&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p id=\"[object]\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\" title=\"[object]\" lang=\"[object]\" onclick=\"[object]\" ondblclick=\"[object]\" onmousedown=\"[object]\" onmouseup=\"[object]\" onmouseover=\"[object]\" onmousemove=\"[object]\" onmouseout=\"[object]\" onkeypress=\"[object]\" onkeydown=\"[object]\" onkeyup=\"[object]\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: \">There is some small pre-work to be completed before arriving at the meeting. I have posted some meeting documents for your review below. The document that started it all is the Hunt 2009 article (2011_TPPT_Jul_05). However, I have gone back into the TPPT archives and found a few more that I have posted here as well. </span></p>\r\n<h3 id=\"[object]\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\" title=\"[object]\" lang=\"[object]\" onclick=\"[object]\" ondblclick=\"[object]\" onmousedown=\"[object]\" onmouseup=\"[object]\" onmouseover=\"[object]\" onmousemove=\"[object]\" onmouseout=\"[object]\" onkeypress=\"[object]\" onkeydown=\"[object]\" onkeyup=\"[object]\">&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p id=\"[object]\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 0pt;\" title=\"[object]\" lang=\"[object]\" onclick=\"[object]\" ondblclick=\"[object]\" onmousedown=\"[object]\" onmouseup=\"[object]\" onmouseover=\"[object]\" onmousemove=\"[object]\" onmouseout=\"[object]\" onkeypress=\"[object]\" onkeydown=\"[object]\" onkeyup=\"[object]\">Before the meeting, please do some research for more information (e.g. supporting or contradicting the Hunt 2009 article, new developments in SF, etc.) so we can have a fruitful discussion on how to move forward with the SF draft treatments and provide some recommendations to the SC in November 2011. If you find some more articles or would like to present a discussion paper, please send them to me by Monday, 4 July, so I can post them in the restricted area for everyone to review before the meeting.</p>','9187'),(759,'**TP on Phytosanitary Treatments: 26-30 July 2010 in Kyoto, Japan**\r\n\r\n\r\nWelcome to the TPPT restricted work area for the upcoming 2010 Kyoto, Japan Meeting. Some meeting documents are already posted on this site and are available for download below. Please check regularly for new documents as there are updates of the existing ones or new posts. The Secretariat of the IPPC invites discussion papers for review at the meeting. Please submit any discussion papers and any supporting documents (regulations, journal articles, etc.) to Mr. Larry Zettler (Larry.Zettler@fao.org) by 16 July 2010. Please bring your own set of documents to the meeting as we will not be able to provide copies at the meeting. Please contact Mr. Zettler with any questions you may have. Thank you for your participation in the standard drafting process and we look forward to working with you.','9111'),(760,'Nine treatments were submitted in response to the call for heat treatment for fruit flies in 2009. All of the submission forms and supporting documents can be found below.','9112'),(761,'<p/>','9127'),(762,'**TP Phytosanitary Treatments 26-30 January 2009, Tokyo, Japan**\r\n\r\n5 February 2009\r\n\r\nDear TPPT members,\r\n\r\nI hope you all had safe flights back to your country. Thank you for your contributions to the TPPT meeting in Tokyo.\r\n\r\nI posted documents distributed during the meeting. A draft meeting report will be sent to you by e-mail later this month.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n20 January 2009\r\n\r\nDear TPPT members,\r\n\r\nTomorrow, 21 January (Wed), is the last day for posting working documents on the IPP.\r\n\r\nPlease make sure that you have the latest versions before leaving for Tokyo as some documents have been revised (shown in the document list as \"2009-TPPT-??-REV?\").\r\n\r\nThere are some documents to be submitted by members. If you need to submit a document after tomorrow, please bring 17 copies for distribution at the meeting.','9091'),(763,'<p/>','9103'),(764,'<p/>','10740'),(765,'17th July 2008\r\n\r\nDear TPPT members\r\n\r\nI have added the amended treatments so you can compare with the versions from December 2007. Please send any comments on the treatments by 14th August.\r\n\r\n14 December 2007\r\n\r\nDear TPPT members\r\n\r\nThe following 11 files files are the treatment descriptions for your review. Minor editorial edjustments have been made from the versions last presented at the Chang Mai meeting, so these files are all labeled as \"REV1\".\r\n\r\nThe document titles correspond to:\r\n\r\nTPPT Document number (submission number) Treatment name','9077'),(766,'**TP Phytosanitary Treatments 3-7 December 2007, Chiang Mai, Thailand**\r\n14th December\r\n\r\nThe treatment descriptions have been posted; please click on \"treatment descriptions\" in the lefthand sidebar to access them.\r\n\r\n12th December\r\n\r\nI hope you all arrived home safely. Thank you for your contributions to the TPPT meeting.\r\n\r\nWe will post the working documents distributed during the meeting as soon as possible. I will also post the checklists as they were modified in the meeting (labelled with \"REV1\", apart from document 30, which is \"REV2\"). I will also post the treatment schedules numbered in the 200 series, with the number matching the origninal submission.\r\n\r\nI have posted the work programme. You will see that some of the deadlines you agreed to were in January, but to help with report writing, if you have the paragraphs for the report done earlier, I would be grateful to receive them as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nRegards, Jane','9069'),(767,'<p/>','9096'),(768,'TP Phytosanitary Treatments 4-8 December 2006, Vienna, Austria\r\n15 December 2006: Update \r\nAs requested, I have posted the checklists for the irradiation treatments. Please note these are the raw documents produced in the meeting - they have not been adjusted or formatted. Adjustments will be made to the schedules that appear in the report.\r\n\r\nWith best wishes for the festive season\r\n\r\nJane','9025'),(769,'Dear TPPT Members,\r\n\r\nI posted the agenda and all meeting documents below. Please email Artur Shamilov or Stephanie Dubon if you have any questions about the meeting. In the case I have any updates relating our meeting I will inform you immediately.\r\n\r\nPlease be kindly informed that once IPPC Secretariat received the access to the Adobe Connect we will allow to organize training meeting with everybody. I will inform you immediatelly. The time of Virtual Meeting on Thursday, April 25, 2013 6:00 AM - 8:00 AM USA EST:\r\n\r\nApproximate meeting times are:\r\n\r\nLate evening: Australia and New Zealand Mid-day: Europe and Africa Early morning: North and South America\r\n\r\nBest regards,\r\n\r\nArtur','14668'),(770,'<p/>','14669'),(771,'<p/>Click [here](/forums/tppt-forum) to see the **Forums**. Click [here](/node/15371) to see the **Archived Forums**. ','15373'),(772,'<p/>','26790'),(773,'When: 23 January 2014 20:00-22:00 (GMT+01:00) Rome time\r\n\r\nThe meeting room will be open 30 minutes prior the meeting time in order to test all your equipments.','27406'),(774,'<p><strong>2014 April TPPT Virtual Meeting</strong></p><p>TPPT virtual meeting &nbsp;will be held &nbsp;<strong>Tuesday, 29 April , 2014 at 10:00:00 PM</strong> (Rome time)&nbsp;</p><p>Please note that some user requirements are needed for Adobe Connect:</p><p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt;\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Internet Explorer:</strong> please make sure to use this browser;</p><p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt;\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Adobe Flash</strong> (latest version available at <a href=\"http://get.adobe.com/flashplayer/\">http://get.adobe.com/flashplayer/</a>);</p><p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt;\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>A USB headset.</strong></p><p>Before connecting, please also try the AC connection test at <a href=\"http://connectpro78383270.adobeconnect.com/common/help/en/support/meeting_test.htm\">http://connectpro78383270.adobeconnect.com/common/help/en/support/meeting_test.htm</a></p><p>In order to login at the meeting&rsquo;s date, you have to copy the meeting&rsquo;s URL into your browser <strong><a href=\"http://fao.adobeconnect.com/tppt2014-04/\" target=\"_blank\">http://fao.adobeconnect.com/tppt2014-04/</a> </strong>, and then select &ldquo;Enter as a Guest&rdquo;, type in your name and enter the room. You do not need to pre-register.</p><p>Further information is available on the IPP at <a href=\"https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/virtual-tools\">https://www.ippc.int/core-activities/standards-setting/virtual-tools</a></p><p><strong>When</strong>: 29 April 2014 22:00-23:59 (GMT+01:00) Rome time</p><p>The meeting room will be open <strong>1 hour</strong> prior the meeting time in order to test all your equipments.&nbsp;</p>','27407'),(775,'**2014 June Bali**\r\n\r\n\r\nDear TPPT Members,\r\n\r\nThe 2014 TPPT Meeting is scheduled for 23-27 June 2014 in Bali, Indonesia.\r\n\r\nDo not hesitate to contact Artur.Shamilov@fao.org  or Nuri.Niyazi@fao.org for questions about the meeting.\r\n\r\nPlease contact Ms Serlina serlina_2974@yahoo.com for any questions regarding travel, hotels, etc.\r\n\r\n**UPDATE:  19 June 2014**\r\n\r\nAll meeting documents that I received have been posted below.\r\n\r\nSome documnets were revised for consistency with agenda items (no changes in the content)\r\n\r\n**If you will be presenting documents (discussion papers, revised checklists, etc.) other than those posted below, please send it to Artur.Shamilov@fao.org as soon as possible AND bring 17 paper copies with you to meeting.** \r\n\r\nThe draft agenda will be revised once all documents are submitted.\r\n\r\nI look forward to seeing everyone on Monday morning, 23 June, at 10:00 am in Bali.\r\n\r\nBest regards,\r\n\r\nArtur\r\n','27408'),(776,'<p/>','9202'),(777,'**RESTRICTED WORK AREA FOR VIEWING AND DOWNLOADING MEETING DOCUMENTS**\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor all meeting documents, there is a list of folders located on the right hand side of this page under Browse my groups. Please click the plus (+) sign by the folder \"Partners\", then the plus sign by the folder \"International Forestry Quarantine Research Group\" and select the meeting date for the documents you would like to view.\r\n\r\nReports from past meetings are posted publicly on the IPP on the [IFQRG public page][1].\r\n\r\nNEXT MEETING:  IFQRG-12\r\n\r\nRome, Italy\r\n\r\nFAO Headquarters\r\n\r\nSeptember 8-12, 2014\r\n\r\nTo register for this meeting, please complete the registration form (when posted) and e-mail it to eallen@nrcan.gc.ca\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: http:///partners/international-organizations/international-forestry-quarantine-research-group','9134'),(778,'International Forestry Quarantine Research Group - 2012 - 10th Meeting work area\r\n\r\n<p/>![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\nPhoto: Clear Inner Vision on Flikr                         \r\n\r\n**Cardiff, Wales\r\nSeptember 17 - 21, 2012**\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/1336664717_wales.jpg','9256'),(779,'International Forestry Quarantine Research Group - \r\n\r\n\r\n![enter image description here][1]<p/>\r\n\r\n**Canberra Australia\r\nSeptember 26 - 30, 2011**\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/dea11c510b.jpg','9208'),(780,'8th meeting of the International Forestry Quarantine Research Group\r\n\r\nOctober 1, 2010\r\n\r\nThe report from this meeting will be posted on the public area (https://www.ippc.int/index.php?id=187394 ). All remaining documents including presentations that have been release for posting will be posted below as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nThank you all for a great meeting!','9135'),(781,'7th meeting of the International Forestry Quarantine Research Group','9136'),(782,'6th meeting of the International Forestry Quarantine Research Group','9138'),(783,'5th meeting of the International Forestry Quarantine Research Group','9137'),(784,'The IFQRG Forum is designed to provide a place for the discussion and clarification of key issues related to the phytosanitary implications of global trade&nbsp;in an&nbsp;informal way. \r\n<h3>FORUM GUIDELINES</h3>\r\nAnyone can ask questions, share concerns, or open a thread.&nbsp; All the same, we emphasise that this is a moderated forum -- posts deemed to be libellous or in poor taste may be removed.\r\nRaising a question on the Forum is easy. If you wish to start a new thread, just click on the category where you want to place it in the first column, give it a title and compose your contribution. We encourage you to include your name and e-mail so that people who want to respond know who they are talking to. This is not essential - you can enter a nom de plume and a fantasy e-mail address in the field indicated if you wish. <i>If you want to join a thread that has already started, just click on \'reply\' and fill the fields in the same way. Te forum is multilingual and you can contribute to debates in whatever language you choose.</i>\r\n\r\n<h6>Click <a href=\"/forums/ifqr-forum\">here</a> to see the FORUM.</h6>','9140'),(785,'**Questions and answers regarding ISPM No. 15**\r\n\r\nThe IPPC Secretariat has received numerous requests for information regarding practical aspects of how to use the wood packaging mark in ISPM No. 15 (Guidelines for regulating wood packaging material in international trade).\r\nThese questions relate to: the registration and use of the mark in the context of intellectual property issues; whether and under what conditions producers or others may use and apply the ISPM No. 15 mark; and the appearance of the mark, and whether particular reproductions of it proposed at the national level are in line with Annex II of ISPM No. 15.\r\nMany of these questions about appearance can be answered by reference to specific provisions of the standard itself. In such cases, the Secretariat may note these provisions in response to individual requests. Examples of these types of questions are provided below.\r\nFor other questions, however, the standard does not appear to provide explicit guidance and issues of interpretation are raised. In this regard, it is emphasized that contracting parties, not the Secretariat, have the responsibility to interpret and implement the standard. Accordingly, while the Secretariat may in some cases identify factors for consideration based on the standard, it is up to the parties to determine whether they are in compliance with the standard. Input from the Secretariat should not be regarded as an official legal interpretation. Consistent with this, commercial users of this standard should contact the National Plant Protection Organization in their country to resolve questions that they might have.\r\nParts 4 - 9 below also provide information on other questions of a practical nature that have been put to the Secretariat regarding the implementation of ISPM No. 15.','9142'),(786,'International Forestry Quarantine Research Group - 2013 - 11th Meeting work area','26756'),(787,'<p/>','28120'),(788,'This is a work area set up for the Invasive Species Liaison Group. We can set up a folder for each meeting we have and post other documents for easy reference.\r\n\r\nPlease let me know if you need additional support.\r\n\r\nBrent\r\nBrent.Larson@fao.org','9203'),(789,'<p/>','9204'),(790,'Phytosanitary Temperature Treatments Expert Group\r\nThe group agreed that any research should focus on the sound scientific reasoning behind each step of development of cold phytosanitary treatments and not detailed prescription conducting of phytosanitary treatment. The ECCT identified a series of issues to be addressed by cold treatment researchers  based on scientific, technical and logistical reasons\r\n\r\nFinally the ECCT participant agreed that work on cold treatments and networking among researchers would be useful and agreed to form a new group that would also cover all temperature phytosanitary treatments. The ECCT participants name this group “Phytosanitary Temperature Treatments Expert Group” and developed a Term of References Rules of Procedures and the scope of this group can be extended for all phytosanitary treatments in order to provide a mechanism where critical phytosanitary treatment issues can be addressed through discussion and collaborative research and providing scientific analysis and review of global phytosanitary treatments issues and new information.\r\n\r\nThe Phytosanitary Temperature Treatments Expert Group established Executive Committee which will be composed of a Chair, two Coordinators (one research and one operations) and a Secretary.','27341'),(791,'<p/>','9030'),(792,'<p/>','9032'),(793,'<p/>','9037'),(794,'<p/>','9060'),(795,'<p/>6th Meeting of the SBDS 2008','9082'),(796,'<p/>Work area for the 2013 SBDS meeting. Documents will be posted as they become available.','14893'),(797,'<p/>Work area for the 2012 SBDS meeting. Documents will be posted as they become available.','14894'),(798,'<p/>Click [here](/forums/sbds-forum) to access the **SBDS Forum**.','15370'),(799,'<p/><p>SBDS July 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Documents will be added as they are available.</p>','27885'),(800,'<h3>Welcome to the National Reporting Page!</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This section of the IPP provides important links to materials to support workshop participants, both during the workshop itself and beyond:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?\r\nid=1110778&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=18&amp;cHash=b5200cc046\">Pre-workshop questionnaire</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=1110870&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0\">Workshop presentations</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=1110778&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=5&amp;cHash=63be0d5485\">Usability testing - navigation</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ippc.int/index.php?id=1110778&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=6&amp;cHash=2c2b4751a3\">Usability testing - data management</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=1110777&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=4&amp;cHash=6991f18a1f\">Form for participant action plans</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=infexch_workshop-eval&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=19&amp;cHash=018d674777\">Workshop evalution form</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ippc.int/index.php?id=1110777&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0&amp;tx_simplesurvey_pi1[showUid]=10&amp;cHash=254e03b78d\">Follow-up questionnaire regarding action plans</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href=\"index.php?id=1110781&amp;no_cache=1&amp;L=0\">Information exchange FAQ</a></li>\r\n<li>Information exchange manual&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>By providing valuable tools, discussions on hot topics, and the latest information, we hope you will find everything you need at your fingertips.</p>','9152'),(801,'Information Exchange FAQ\r\n\r\n<b>How do countries adhere to the International Plant Protection Convention?</b>\r\n\r\nCountries that are not contracting parties to the IPPC and who wish to become so, need to deposit (submit) their instrument of adherence to the IPPC with the Director General of FAO. Go to the following URL to access the model instrument of adherence: https://www.ippc.int/file_uploaded/1273491521_MODELINSTRUMENTS_rev_2010_ALL_LA.doc\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>How much does membership to the IPPC cost?</b>\r\n\r\nNothing!\r\n\r\nThe International Plant Protection Convention does not require member countries to pay any fees.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Who should sign the Instrument of Adherence?</b>\r\n\r\nWho signs the letter of adherence to the IPPC is an internal legal issue - essentially it is the person who has legal authority to sign onto conventions on behalf of a country.\r\n\r\nThe instrument of adherence is usually by signed by the Head of State, the Head of the Government, the Minister of Foregin Affairs, or the Minister / Officer who is responsible for signing international treaties on behalf of the government (for example the Minister of Agriculture).\r\n\r\nSometimes governments need authority / approval from parliament before they can sign such new conventions.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>When adhering to the IPPC, who should receive the Instrument of Adherence?</b>\r\n\r\nThe original (including original signature and national stamp) of the Instrument of Adherence must be sent to the Director General of FAO:\r\n\r\n\r\nMr. Jacques Diouf\r\nDirector General of FAO\r\nFood and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, \r\nViale delle Terme di Caracalla, \r\n00153 Rome \r\nItaly\r\n\r\nCommunications regarding the submission of the Instrument of adherence should be copied to:\r\n\r\n- The Secretary of the IPPC - IPPC@fao.org \r\n- The FAO Legal Service\r\n- FAOR in the country or the Regional/Sub-regional FAO representative\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>What are the steps for an Instrument of Adherence to be accepted?</b>\r\n\r\nStep 1: The original instrument is received by the Director General.\r\n\r\nStep 2: The Legal Service performs the functions for depositing the Instrument (includes registering adherence).\r\n\r\nStep 3: Formal communication is made to the country of acceptance of its Instrument of Adherence.\r\n\r\nStep 4: The world is notified of the adherence of the country through the International Phytosanitary Portal (IPP – www.ippc.int).\r\n\r\nStep 5: The CPM announces the new contracting party at the meeting of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures following the date of adherence by the country.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>How can I find a list of all contracting parties of the Convention?</b>\r\n\r\nThe list of parties, the dates which they adhered and all declarations and reservations are given on the webpage of the FAO Legal Office: www.fao.org/Legal/TREATIES/004s-e.htm\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Why are some contact points listed as being \"unofficial\"?</b>\r\n\r\nAn \"Unofficial contact point\" represents a contracting party but has failed to comply with one of the criteria for the designation of an official contact point (e.g. the IPPC Secretariat was not informed of the change in contact point through someone more senior in the government, more than one person was nominated, the contact point is self-appointed)\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Why are there more contact points listed than there are contracting parties?</b>\r\n\r\nSome territories have designated contact points.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>The IPPC contact point for my country has changed. What steps are required to notify the Secretariat of the new contact point?</b>\r\n\r\nArticle VIII.2 of the Convention requires contracting parties to designate a contact point, and therefore it is the contracting party which is responsible for making, and informing the Secretariat of, the nomination.\r\n\r\nClick here to open a form for notifying the IPPC Secretariat of a new contact point.\r\n\r\nThe contracting party, by making the nomination, agrees that the nominee has the necessary authority to fulfil the functions of the contact point as determined within the framework of the IPPC, consequently the notification of the new contact point must be signed by the relevant person more senior than the new IPPC contact point.\r\n\r\nIndividual persons cannot appoint themselves as contact points.\r\n\r\nThere can be only one contact point per contracting party.\r\n\r\nClick here for more information on the Role of Contact Points.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>I have received unroutable error messages when sending email messages to an IPPC contact point. Would it be possible to update the emails on the contact lists?</b>\r\n\r\nNational contact points are responsible for maintaining their own information up-to-date.\r\n\r\nWhenever communication problems are identified, notify the IPPC Secretariat and we will liaise with the NPPO to ensure that the contact information is up-to-date.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n<b>I want to receive only electronic correspondence (no hard copies). How do I indicate this preference?</b>\r\n\r\nContact points and IPP editors are able to indicate their correspondence preference using the IPP.\r\n\r\nTo opt to receive electronic correspondence only: \r\n1. Login to the IPP.\r\n2. Click on the link \"Edit correspondence format\" (in the box labelled \"My preferences\"). \r\n3. Follow the steps on the next screen and submit the form.\r\n\r\nIt is possible to change correspondence preferences at any time.\r\n\r\nPlease note that the IPPC Secretariat is taking steps to go paperless by 2012.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>How do I change the password for my IPP user account?</b>\r\n\r\nTo change your password: \r\n1. Login to the IPP. This opens your dashboard \r\n2. Click on the link \"Change my Password\" (in the box labelled \"My preferences\"). \r\n3. Follow the steps on the next screen.\r\n\r\nPlease note the your new password must meet the following criteria: \r\n- at least 6 characters long;\r\n- does not contain your username; amd\r\n- contains characters from three of the following categories :\r\n\r\ncontains at least one number \r\ncontains at least one uppercase and one lowercase characters (a through z)\r\ncontains at least one non-alphabetic character (e.g. . , ; : * % ! ~ - + = ^ ?” )\r\n\r\n<b>My contact information has changed. How can I update it?</b>\r\n\r\nIPP account holders are responsible for maintaining their own information up-to-date.\r\n\r\nFollow these steps to update your contact information.\r\n1. Login to the IPP.\r\n2. In the box labelled \"My contact information\", click on the edit button.\r\n3. Use the form to update your contact information. Required fields are marked with an asterisk.\r\n4. Once the updates have been made, click on the \"Submit\" button at the bottom of the form.\r\n\r\nPlease note that the following fields can only be edited by the IPPC Secretariat: Type of contact, Contact Name, Title/position, Date Nomination Received and the Source of information. If the information in these fields is not correct, contact the IPPC Secretariat (ippc@fao.org).\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>What is an \"IPP editor\"?</b>\r\n\r\nThe International Phytosanitary Portal (IPP) is an internet-based information system designed to hold official phytosanitary information published in accordance with the Convention and decisions by the CPM. The objective is to provide a single portal to official phytosanitary information and to facilitate IPPC contracting parties to meet their reporting obligations under the IPPC.\r\n\r\nNational data can be entered into the IPP by the Official Contact Point. IPPC Contact Points can also nominate IPP editors to undertake data entry on their behalf.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>I am the IPPC contact point for a country. How can I nominate an IPP editor?</b>\r\n\r\nTo nominate a new IPP editor, the IPPC contact point must complete the nomination form and submit it to the IPPC Secretariat (ippc@fao.org).\r\n\r\nClick here to access the form for nominating new IPP editors.\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>I would like to notify my trading partners of new information that I have reported through the IPP. How do I do this?</b>\r\n\r\nA section at the bottom of all forms for national reporting enables IPPC Contact Points and Editors to directly notify selected recipients whenever they make changes or additions to their NPPO page. \r\n\r\nPotential recipients of these notifications include the IPPC Official Contact Point for trading partner nations, representatives of RPPOs, and the IPPC Secretariat. Once selected, recipients will automatically receive an email notifying them when a change has been made to the NPPO webpage along with a link to the part of the NPPO page that has been modified.  In this way, the selected recipients are made aware of updates to contact information, the addition of pest reports, the publication of phytosanitary regulations, etc, and this is more consistent with the reporting requirements of the IPPC.\r\n\r\nTo use the Notification tool, please follow these steps: \r\n1. Login to the IPP.\r\n\r\n2. Open the form to add or update information.\r\n\r\n3. At the bottom of the form is a section labelled the “Notifications Tool”\r\n\r\nIf you wish to notify others of the availability of new information, you must select recipients the first time you use the notification tool. Your selection will then be saved as your default recipient list.\r\nOnce you have selected your default recipient list, to send out notifications in the future you can select Yes, send to default recipients.\r\nIf you do not want to notify others of changes, select No, submit without notification.\r\n4. Click submit\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Where can I find information on countries implementing ISPM 15?</b>\r\n\r\nMany countries have provided specific answers to the following questions: \r\n\r\nwhether ISPM 15 has been implemented for imports or exports and if so, which version (2002 or 2009);\r\nwhether wood packaging is regulated differently than outlined in ISPM 15;\r\nwhether the mark has been registered in the country; where to find national legislation and/or relevant websites; and\r\nwho to contact for more information regarding ISPM 15.\r\nThis information has been compiled into a single, easy access table.\r\n\r\nClick here to view the table with information on countries’ implementation of ISPM 15. \r\n\r\nIPPC contact points are able to respond to information requests and communicate on phytosanitary issues on behalf of their country.\r\n\r\nClick here to access a list of official contact information for NPPOs. \r\n\r\nRelated entries:\r\n\r\nWhere can I find information on countries implementing ISPM 15?','9162'),(802,'<p/>','9205'),(803,'<p/>','27883'),(804,'<h3>First Meeting of the NROAG 2014-07-01</h3>\r\n\r\n<strong>Dates:</strong> 1 - 3 July 2014</p><p><strong>Venue:</strong> Pakistan Room, FAO, Rome, Italy</p><hr /><p>This is the first meeting of the NROAG that is tasked with providing the Secretariat with advice regarding the revision of the IPPC National Reporting Obligations programme.</p><p>Documents for this meeting are not public but the report of the meeting will be in the public domain.</p><hr /><p><u>Documents and the meeting will be in English only as agreed by CPM.</u></p>','27884'),(805,'<p/>','28029'),(806,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\nKingwing Hot Spring Int\'l Hotel Beijing, China 26 October – 28 October 2010\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\nTarget audience: NPPO staff –\r\n\r\n- IPP editors (individuals responsible for loading information on to the IPP)\r\n- Translators\r\n- Staff who provide support to information exchange\r\n- Staff who refer to information provided by the Secretariat or other NPPOs (e.g. standards, draft standards, pest reports, regulated pests lists, phytosanitary restrictions)\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/1288161891_group.jpg','9183'),(807,'<h1>Workshop on information exchange under the IPPC & the use of the International Phytosanitary Portal - Southern African countries</h1>\r\n![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n\r\nPro-Active College, Brooklyn, Pretoria, South Africa\r\n26 September – 01 October 2010\r\n\r\n\r\nDuring the SADC Plant Protection Committee Meeting of 2009 and also at the 5th Session of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures (CPM-5) held in Rome in March 2010, the SADC Secretariat was requested to convene a workshop to train officers from the NPPOs on the use of the International Phytosanitary Portal. The purpose of the workshop is to explain national phytosanitary information exchange obligations under the Convention and to provide training on how Contact Point and/or nominated IPP editors can use the IPP to meet national reporting obligations.\r\n\r\nWorkshop documents are given below. It is also possible to access the online forms for usability testing, action planning and evaluating the workshop using the righthand navigation menu.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/1285837576_sadc-inf_exch_workshop-group_pho.jpg','9179'),(808,'**Taller de Capacitación para el Intercambio de Información y el Uso del Sitio Web de la CIPF**\r\n\r\n\r\nInstituto Colombiano Agropecuario\r\nBogota, Colombia\r\n18 – 21 mayo 2010\r\n \r\n \r\n \r\n \r\nAGENDA\r\n \r\nMartes, 18 mayo 2010 \r\nApertura del taller\r\nElección del relator\r\n\r\nPresentaciones:\r\n\r\n- Objetivos y resultados previstos del taller\r\n- Panorama de la CIPF\r\n- El intercambio de información\r\n\r\n	- El papel del punto de contacto de la CIPF y la difusión de información oficial\r\n	- Descripción de la Organización de Protección Fitosanitaria\r\n	- Acuerdos organizacionales de protección fitosanitaria\r\n	- Puntos de ingreso\r\n	- Requisitos, restricciones y prohibiciones fitosanitarias\r\n \r\n- Ejercicios prácticos de navegación por el Portal\r\n \r\nMiercoles, 19 Mayo 2010 \r\n\r\nPresentaciones  \r\n\r\n- Función y relación de la información científica y oficial\r\n- La CIPF y el Acuerdo MSF\r\n- Encuestas sobre plagas & listas de plagas reglamentadas\r\n	- NIMF 6 (Directrices para la vigilancia)\r\n- Estado de una plaga en una área\r\n	 - NIMF 8 (Determinación de la situación de una plaga en un área)\r\n- Informe oficial sobre plagas\r\n	 - NIMF 17 (Notificación de plagas)\r\n- Listas de plagas reglamentadas\r\n	 - NIMF 19 (Directrices sobre las listas de plagas reglamentadas)\r\n \r\n \r\nJueves, 20 Mayo 2010 \r\n\r\nPresentaciones sobre otros tipos de información que las CNPF pueden comunicar a través del Portal\r\n\r\n- Procedimiento normativo CIPF\r\n- Áreas libres de plagas\r\n\r\n	- NIMF 04 (Requisitos para el establecimiento de áreas libres de plagas)\r\n\r\n\r\nContinuación con ejercicios prácticos con el Portal y el manejo de información\r\nProcesos del intercambio de información a nivel nacional\r\nDialogo sobre recomendaciones para los próximos pasos y formulación de los planes de acción\r\nPresentaciones por los participantes sobre la información en las páginas de sus países y los planes de acción\r\nEvaluación y clausura del taller','9153'),(809,'<p/>','9168'),(810,'<p/>','9156'),(811,'<p/>','9154'),(812,'<p/>','9158'),(813,'<p/>','9120'),(814,'<h3>LinkedIn</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/groups/IPPC-International-Plant-Protection-Convention-3175642?trk=mygugrpovr\">http://www.linkedin.com/groups/IPPC-International-Plant-Protection-Convention-3175642?trk=myg</a><em style=\"margin-top: 0px;\"><a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/groups/IPPC-International-Plant-Protection-Convention-3175642?trk=mygugrpovr\">ugrp</a></em><a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/groups/IPPC-International-Plant-Protection-Convention-3175642?trk=mygugrpovr\">ovr</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Flickr / Yahoo</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Yahoo ID: ippcwebmaster@yahoo.com</li>\r\n<li>Password:&nbsp;badverybad&hellip;&nbsp;(ask simon)</li>\r\n<li>Flickr Acount URL: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ippc\">http://www.flickr.com/photos/ippc</a></li>\r\n<li>IPPC Group URL:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/international_plant_protection_convention/\">http://www.flickr.com/groups/international_plant_protection_convention/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Facebook</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>FAO: <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Food-and-Agriculture-Organization-of-the-United-Nations-FAO/46370758585\">http://www.facebook.com/pages/Food-and-Agriculture-Organization-of-the-United-Nations-FAO/46370758585</a></li>\r\n<li>IPPC (?): <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/International-Plant-Protection-Convention/137672612922945\">http://www.facebook.com/pages/International-Plant-Protection-Convention/137672612922945</a></li>\r\n<li>IPPC Group:&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: medium; font-family: Times;\"><a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/home.php?sk=group_100412373382922\">http://www.facebook.com/home.php?sk=group_100412373382922</a></span></li>\r\n<li>User: ippcwebmaster</li>\r\n<li>Pass: badverybad&hellip; (ask simon)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Twitter</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://twitter.com/#!/ippcnews\">http://twitter.com/ippcnews</a></li>\r\n<li>Yahoo ID: ippcwebmaster@yahoo.com</li>\r\n<li>Password:&nbsp;badverybad&hellip;&nbsp;(ask simon)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-weight: bold;\">Google &amp; Analytics</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>http://gmail.com</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://google.com/analytics\">http://google.com/analytics</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://plus.google.com/u/0/b/105398609011714435570/105398609011714435570/posts\">https://plus.google.com/u/0/b/105398609011714435570/105398609011714435570/posts</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>YouTube</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>http://www.youtube.com/user/IPPCnews</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo ID: ippcwebmaster@yahoo.com</li>\r\n<li>Password:&nbsp;badverybad&hellip;&nbsp;(ask simon)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','9207'),(815,'<div class=\"csc-textpic csc-textpic-center csc-textpic-below csc-textpic-border\"><div class=\"csc-textpic-text\">The is currently facing a budget crisis. \r\nThe 2011 budget estimates (USD) required to operate a similar work programme to that in 2010, are $4,947,000. The funds available at the moment for 2011 are $3,701,000, meaning the anticipated shortfall is <b><i>$1,246,000</i></b>. As a consequence significant cuts are proposed in all of the \'s activities. Click on the graphs below to view the funds that have been committed for 2011 and how the shortfall in funds will affect each of the goals. \r\n<span lang=\"EN-NZ\">In particular, to allow minimum work on these priorities to continue, the following programme reductions have been made:</span>\r\n<ul><li><span lang=\"EN-NZ\"><span><span><span>a basic CPM meeting;</span></span></span></span></li><li><span lang=\"EN-NZ\"><span><span><span>a May SC7 meeting;</span></span></span></span></li><li><span lang=\"EN-NZ\"><span><span><span>a November SC7 meeting and</span></span></span></span></li><li><span lang=\"EN-NZ\"><span><span><span>a small resource mobilisation programme</span></span></span></span><span><span lang=\"EN-NZ\">.</span></span><b><span lang=\"EN-NZ\"><span>&nbsp;</span></span></b></li></ul>\r\n<b><span lang=\"EN-NZ\">What contracting parties can do?</span></b> \r\n<span lang=\"EN-NZ\">The will only be able to carry out its programme of work if it receives&nbsp;extra-budgetary support. With contributions, some activities could be reinstated, for example extra-budgetary funds would facilitate:</span>\r\n<ul><li><span><span lang=\"EN-NZ\">evening sessions for CPM<span> to discuss draft standards (</span>$50,000);</span></span></li><li><span><span lang=\"EN-NZ\">a full SC meeting in November ($130,000) and</span></span></li><li><span><span lang=\"EN-NZ\">Technical Panel meetings, including consultant support ($150,000).</span></span></li></ul>\r\n<span lang=\"EN-NZ\">This is the minimum funding required to continue the standards setting programme and contracting parties are invited to also contribute to the capacity building, information exchange and resource mobilisation programmes.</span> \r\n<link 1111007 - internal-link \"Opens internal link in current window\">Click here to learn more about the contributors that help make the <acronym title=\"International Plant Protection Convention\">IPPC</acronym> possible.</link> </div></div>','9216'),(816,'<div class=\"csc-header csc-header-n1\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"csc-textpic-text\">\r\nRegular programme funding from the  does not&nbsp;cover the full operating costs associated with delivery of the  work programme in any given year.\r\nContributions from governments and&nbsp;international organizations are essential for the  to be able to carry forward the  mission to &quot;protect the world\'s plant resources from pests&quot;.\r\nThe  would like to express its appreciation to the following donors for their generous support to our work in 2010 (click on the links to learn more about what contributions make possible):\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<ul><li><strong>Australia</strong></li></ul>\r\n<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"index.php?id=1110798&amp;tx_news_pi1[showUid]=1106111&amp;frompage=1110664&amp;type=news&amp;subtype=&amp;L=0#item\">Support to  communications and advocacy programme.</a>\r\n<ul><li><strong>European Union</strong></li></ul>\r\n<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"index.php?id=1110798&amp;tx_news_pi1[showUid]=1106100&amp;frompage=1110664&amp;type=news&amp;subtype=&amp;L=0#item\">Assistance for the participation of developing countries in  meetings.</a>\r\n<ul><li><strong>Japan</strong></li><li><strong>New Zealand</strong></li></ul>\r\n<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"index.php?id=1110798&amp;tx_news_pi1[showUid]=1106105&amp;frompage=1110664&amp;type=news&amp;subtype=&amp;L=0#item\">Expert working group (EWG) to prepare a draft standard on &quot;Minimizing pest movement by sea containers and conveyances in international trade&quot;.</a>\r\n<ul><li>USA((??))</li></ul></blockquote></div>','9217'),(817,'This is the page for the Expert Working Group on Resource Mobilisation, which will be convened in September 2010.','9218'),(818,'<p/>','9263'),(819,'<p/>','9264'),(820,'<p/>','9124'),(821,'<p/>','14694'),(822,'<p>During the <span lang=\"NL\">IPPC OEWG on Electronic Certification</span> in June 2011, the OEWG established 3 working groups to further develop standardised procedurs, processes and codes tht could be utlized for the electronic transmission of phytosanitary certificates (ePhytos). In order to facilitate the work of these working groups, this work area has been established. These working groups are:</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"hover\"><strong>Working Group 1</strong>: IPPC XML Schema and ISPM 12 mapping.</span></p>\r\n<p>Leader:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"hover\"><strong>Working Group 2</strong>: Harmonization of ISPM 12 Code Lists.</span></p>\r\n<p>Leader: Nico Horn</p>\r\n<p><br /><span class=\"hover\"><strong>Working Group 3</strong>: Harmonization of data exchange and security protocols.</span></p>\r\n<p>Leader:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Outcomes from these working groups will be summarized and the core standard procedures will be fed into the IPPC standard setting process for possible inclusion as an Appendix in ISPM 12, 2011.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','9209'),(823,'Work area for the activities of Working Group 1: IPPC XML Schema and ISPM 12 mapping.','9210'),(824,'The work area for Working Group 2: Harmonization of ISPM 12 Code Lists activities.','9212'),(825,'The work area for \"Working Group 3: Harmonization of data exchange and security protocols\" activities.','9214'),(826,'This page is the work area for the ePhyto Expert Working Group: September 2012.','9253'),(827,'The \"United Nations Code for Trade and Transport Locations\" is commonly more known as \"UN/LOCODE\". Although managed and maintained by the UNECE, it is the product of a wide collaboration in the framework of the joint trade facilitation effort undertaken within the United Nations.\r\n\r\nInitiated within the UNECE Working Party on Trade Facilitation, UN/LOCODE is based on a code structure set up by UN/ECLAC and a list of locations originating in UN/ESCAP, developed in UNCTAD in co-operation with transport organisations like IATA and the ICS and with active contributions from national governments and commercial bodies. Its first issue in 1981 provided codes to represent the names of some 8.000 locations in the world.\r\n\r\nAs of April 2012, UN/LOCODE includes over 83,000 locations in 243 countries and installations in international waters. It is used by most major shipping companies, by freight forwarders and in the manufacturing industry around the world. It is also applied by national governments and in trade related activities, such as statistics where it is used by the European Union, by the UPU for certain postal services, etc','9254'),(828,'**Core Group to develop the Guide to implementation of phytosanitary standards in forestry**\r\n\r\n![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n\r\nGreetings all! Welcome to the work area for the FAO Forestry Guide to implementation of phytosanitary standards in forestry.\r\n\r\nsee more...\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/8ea1fd09e2.jpg','9182'),(829,'<p/>','9184'),(830,'<p/>','9072'),(831,'IPPC social media links and login information:','9206'),(832,'This area is an area to be used by the IPP SG to test the functions and usability of the IPP. It is not in the public domain, so people without a password (outside the IPP SG) cannot see this area. There are 2 major areas that needs careful examination:\r\n\r\nUser interface\r\nThis applies to the whole website. Initialy this can be undertaken without logging into the system. However, the same exercise can be repeated once you have logged in (navigation behaviour can be different, although unlikely. To make it easier, we shall provide a list of things to check - how you check this function is up to you. There are 3 components to using a website on which we would appreciate feedback: navigation, layout / structure and content. These all contribute to useability.\r\n\r\nData entry\r\nThis applies only to editors of various categories and can only be undertaken once you have logged into the IPPC website.Â  Again to make it easier, we shall provide you with a list of functionality that needs checking. We are particularly interested in bugs (especially those that make the system unusable), clarity and easy of use, and functionality.\r\n\r\nFeedback\r\nFeedback is always appreciate at all times. Major bugs will get attention immediately, but normally comments are collected, analyzed and then periodically the site will be adjusted to reflect a consensus of all the feedback.\r\n\r\nWe will also provide a form to help standardise the feedback to the Secretariat. When you provide feedback on bugs / errors, please always include: the URL, if possible the exact text from any error message and a brief description of what happened.','9029'),(833,'This is the root for VWGs','9126'),(834,'<p/>','9172'),(835,'Work area for the development of a draft document detailing a mentoring strategy for the IPPC.','9093'),(836,'This is the work area for the small group that is drafting a document listing principles for effective phytosanitary capacity building.','9092'),(837,'<p/>','26485'),(838,'**Dear participants for the Task Force meeting, greetings!**\r\n\r\nPlease note the documents posted below.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">LATEST DOCUMENTS POSTED: Updated documents posted on 2013-09-13:</a><br></div> \r\n\r\n- 01_TF_2013_Sep: Provisional Agenda \r\n \r\n- 02_TF_2013_Sep: Documents list \r\n\r\n- 13_TF_2013_Sep: Review of IRSS studies\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">Logistics Information</a><br></div> \r\n\r\nLocal: Residence Inn by Marriott Ottawa Downtown\r\n\r\nOttawa, Ontario, CANADA\r\n\r\nRoom: MONTCALM, (2nd floor)\r\n\r\n- 18 September start time: 10:00 hrs (welcome coffee at 09:30hrs)\r\n\r\n- Daily Schedule: 09:00-12:30 and 14:00-17:30\r\n\r\n- Coffee: Wednesday welcome coffee 9:30 and 15:30. Rest of the week at 10:30 and 15:30\r\n\r\n- 18 September: Dinner at 19:00\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Updated documents posted on 2013-09-09:**\r\n\r\n- 01_TF_2013_Sep: Provisional Agenda \r\n \r\n- 02_TF_2013_Sep: Documents list \r\n\r\n- 11_TF_2013_Sep: United States Discussion Paper\r\n\r\n- 12_TF_2013_Sep: Overview of the concept of log frames - Logical Framework\r\n\r\n\r\n**Updated documents posted on 2013-09-03:**\r\n\r\n- 01_TF_2013_Sep: Provisional Agenda \r\n \r\n- 02_TF_2013_Sep: Documents list \r\n\r\n- 09_TF_2013_Sep: Concept note: nature of a standard\r\n\r\n- 10-A_TF_2013_Sep: A consideration of frameworks for IPPC ISPMs\r\n\r\n- 10-B_TF_2013_Sep: Forum summary for SC e-decision\r\n\r\n**Updated documents posted on 2013-09-02:**\r\n\r\n- 01_TF_2013_Sep: Provisional Agenda \r\n \r\n- 02_TF_2013_Sep: Documents list \r\n\r\n- 08_TF_2013_Sep: Framework for International Standards \r\n\r\n**Updated documents posted on 2013-08-20:**\r\n\r\n- 01_TF_2013_Sep: Provisional Agenda \r\n \r\n- 02_TF_2013_Sep: Documents list \r\n\r\n- 06_TF_2013_Sep: Concept paper: Purpose, status and content of ISPMs\r\n\r\n- 07-A_TF_2013_Sep: Reorganization of ISPMs \r\n\r\n- 07-B_TF_2013_Sep: Reorganization of ISPMs: Consultant’s Report\r\n\r\n- 07-C_TF_2013_Sep: Reorganization of ISPMs: OIE Terrestrial Animal Health Standards\r\n\r\n\r\n**Updated Participants List (03_TF_2013_Sep) posted on 2013-08-12**\r\n\r\n\r\n**Other documents:**\r\n\r\n- 04_TF_2013_Sep: Local information_Rev1 \r\n\r\n- 05_TF_2013_Sep: Overview of the creation of a Task Force to develop a framework for IPPC standards.\r\n\r\nOnce again, **The IPPC Secretariat is soliciting discussion paper submissions for the upcoming meeting on the Framework for Standards Task Force. Submissions of discussion papers should be sent to the IPPC Secretariat by e-mail (ippc@fao.org) no later than 30 August 2013. (Note: Late submissions will not be accepted).**\r\n\r\nFor the TF meeting participants, you can e-mail directly to Adriana.Moreira@fao.org ','26486'),(839,'<p/>The Expert Consultation on Cold Treatments (ECCT) will provide a forum for discussion of issues related to the development and use of cold treatments and allow participants to build confidence in the experimental design and science supporting cold treatments, help establish mutual understanding of related issues and provide a platform for initiating future synergies among cold treatment developers. Invited experts would be expected to provide an overview of cold treatments they have developed and/or used and to identify the main issues that need to be considered when developing, evaluating and implementing such treatments. Cold treatment experts with experience in designing and conducting research as well as those involved in the practical implementation of these cold treatments should participate in this consultation. The ECCT will be held in Buenos Aires (Argentina) from 2 to 6 December 2013. ','26803'),(840,'![<p/>][1]\r\n\r\n**Dear Participant of the Expert Consultation on Cold Treatment (ECCT)**\r\n\r\n**WELCOME** to our work area!\r\n\r\n\r\nThe ECCT meeting is organized by IPPC Secretariat and hosted by Argentina NPPO. The ECCT will provide a forum for discussion of issues related to the development and use of cold treatments and allow participants to build confidence in the experimental design and science supporting cold treatments, help establish mutual understanding of related issues and provide a platform for initiating future synergies among cold treatment developers.\r\n\r\n\r\nInvited experts would be expected to provide an overview of cold treatments they have developed and/or used and to identify the main issues that need to be considered when developing, evaluating and implementing such treatments. Cold treatment experts with experience in designing and conducting research as well as those involved in the practical implementation of these cold treatments should participate in this consultation. \r\n\r\n\r\nThe meeting will be held on Amerian Hotel from 02 to 06 December 2013.\r\n\r\n\r\nA provisional agenda will be posted soon.\r\n\r\n\r\nAs outlined in the call for experts, you submitted an abstract of the proposed presentation and you are now invited to deliver a presentation that should last no more than 15 minutes. **Please send the presentation and discussion papers to the IPPC Secretariat to Mr Shamilov (Artur.Shamilov@fao.org) no later than 4 November 2013.** \r\n\r\n\r\nSee you all in Buenos Aires in December!\r\n\r\n\r\nKind regards, \r\n\r\nIPPC Secretariat.\r\n\r\n\r\n*The IPPC Secretariat contact for this meeting is Mr Artur Shamilov. Any queries, please e-mail him at Artur.Shamilov@fao.org*\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/ecct_to_ipp_workarea_web.jpg','27016'),(841,'<p/>','28023'),(842,'![enter image description here][1]\r\n\r\n**Dear participants for the Task Force meeting, greetings!**\r\n\r\nYou are invited to post your comments on the **e-Forum** in which the Secretariat opened with suggestions for the main steps to perform a situational analysis and to identify the main gaps at the meeting. \r\n\r\n\r\n[Click here](https://www.ippc.int/forums/fseforum01-2014-framework-standards-meeting-%E2%80%93-costa-rica) to access the e-Forum link. \r\n\r\n\r\nNote that we are not asking for answers to the questions but your comments and thoughts. \r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\nIPPC Secretariat.\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"warning floatcenter\">Logistics Information</a><br></p> \r\n\r\nMeeting dates: 25 to 29 August 2014.\r\n\r\nLocal: [Punta Leona Beach Hotel](http://hotelpuntaleona.com/)\r\n\r\nCentral Pacific Coast, COSTA RICA\r\n\r\n\r\nMeeting start time on Monday 25 August: 10:00 hrs \r\n\r\nDaily Schedule: 09:00-11:00 and 14:00-16:00\r\n\r\n*Time between meetings will be used for group and individual exercises.*\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**NOTE:** \r\n\r\nThe hotel designated for Saturday 23 August overnight in San Jose is Hotel City Express Aeropuerto. The hotel website can be reached by [clicking here.](http://cityexpress.hotelescity.com/es/hoteles/city-express-san-jose-aeropuerto-costa-rica/informacion-general.aspx?hoteldatos=0CECESJO)\r\n\r\nPlease provide your flight details to Ms. Tanja Lahti (tanja.lahti@fao.org) copying the OIRSA contact persons in the Local Information document, so that the booking and transportation from the airport to the hotel can be arranged in time.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\" role=\"alert\">Time for creativity</a><br></div> \r\n\r\nThe development of a framework encompasses a very thoughtful and creative approach. Please see the videos about the creativity process and enjoy! (links are provided below).\r\n\r\n\r\n- [John Cleese - how to inspire creativity within yourselves](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nu2oOrBkVoQ)\r\n\r\n\r\n- [John Cleese - the origin of creativity](http://www.openculture.com/2010/09/john_cleese_on_the_origin_of_creativity.html)\r\n\r\n\r\n  [1]: /static/media/uploads/workareapages/10eighty-team.png','28303'),(843,'**Development of the Framework for IPPC Standards Forum**\r\n\r\n\r\nClick here to see the Forums.','28380'),(844,'Documents for this meeting will be available on or about July 18, 2014. The most relevant document at this time is from the 9th meeting of the Commission on Phytosanitary Measures, available at [here](files/documents/20140303/cpm_2014_20_rev1_strengthening_implementation_ippc_ispms_en_201403031649--449.09%20KB.pdf).\r\n\r\nDocuments pour la réunion seront disponibles vers le 18 Juillet, 2014. Le document le plus pertinent en ce moment est de la 9ème réunion de la Commission des mesures phytosanitaires, disponible à ce [lien](files/documents/20140303/cpm_2014_20_rev1_strengthening_implementation_ippc_ispms_en_201403031649--449.09%20KB.pdf).','28179'),(846,'\r\n**OEWG Implementation - August 4-7, 2014**\r\n\r\n\r\n**Open ended working group (OEWG) - Implementation**\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOver the period of implementation of the Implementation Review and Support system (IRSS) (2011-2014) and, through other IPPC activities, it has been repeatedly noted that CPs face continuing implementation challenges in achieving IPPC objectives. At CPM-8, New Zealand presented a proposal for focusing more on broadening work on implementation of the IPPC and ISPMs and establishing a CPM-directed implementation programme.\r\n\r\nSince CPM-8 (2013) discussions have been held in the Bureau and SPG meetings to consider this new focus of work. The CPM-9 agreed to strengthen the focus on implementation, recognizing that this will require strong commitment from each CPM member and the Secretariat, as well as additional financial resources.\r\n\r\nBased on CP feedback a terms of reference (ToR) for an Open Ended Working Group (OEWG) on Implementation has been prepared. The objective is to establish the required mechanisms to focus on implementation, and ensure the work of the Secretariat staff and CPM bodies are able to be coordinated and work together to deliver a coherent programme of work.\r\n\r\nThe OEWG is also tasked to develop and define the scope of a pilot work plan to implement ISPM 6:1997(Guidelines for surveillance) (2009-004) and to submit a strategic work plan to CPM-10 (2015) for approval.\r\n\r\nThe outcome of the OEWG will be shared with the SPG, subsidiary bodies and the CDC as necessary, and a report back to CPM-10 (2015) will be made. \r\n\r\nDocument 1 \"OEWG Implementation meeting preparation form\" is provided for participants to prepare for the meeting. ','28426'),(847,'<p/>','28288'),(848,'The home page for the IPPC Financial Committee for the First meeting in June 2012.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n**2012-06-14:** All Documents have been uploaded with the exception of 8 and 10 which have been cancelled.\r\n\r\nThe meeting will start on Friday 15 June at 10:00 AM and will be held in the FAO Room B-640.','9258'),(849,'<p/>','9267'),(850,'<p/>','15619'),(851,'<p/>','20428'),(852,'<p/>','26947'),(853,'<p/>','27769'),(854,'<p/>','28183'),(855,'<p/>','28570'),(859,'.',''),(883,'<p/>',''),(885,'The Joint FAO/IAEA Programme assists Member Countries of FAO and IAEA to use nuclear techniques and related biotechnologies for developing improved strategies for sustainable food security.\r\n<p>\r\nThe Food and Environmental Protection Section of the Joint FAO/IAEA Division of Nuclear Techniques in Food and Agriculture, recognizing the importance of the use of irradiation as a quarantine treatment in the American region, has decided to organize a regional workshop on this subject. The Workshop will be held at the General Directorate for Plant Health, M&eacute;xico City, D.F. from 1st to 5th October 2007.\r\n<p>\r\nThe workshop will be aimed mainly at senior officials from the American region who are responsible for policies and regulations in the area of phytosanitary measures for food, as well as quarantine officials, representatives of regional plant protection organizations, professionals, and exporters and importers working in related areas. The workshop is open to professionals from Member States of FAO and the International Atomic Energy Agency ( IAEA). The nominees should come from governments or regional institutions.',''),(886,'documents','20599'),(887,'documents','26000'),(888,'-','28594'),(889,'<p/>','28598'),(890,'<p/>',''),(891,'<p/>',''),(892,'<p/>',''),(893,'<p/>',''),(894,'<p/>',''),(895,'<p/>',''),(896,'<p/>',''),(897,'<p/>',''),(898,'<p/>',''),(899,'<p/>',''),(900,'<p/>',''),(901,'<p/>',''),(902,'<p/>',''),(903,'<p/>',''),(904,'<p/>',''),(905,'<p/>',''),(906,'<p/>','');
